# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The **107% rule** is a sporting regulation affecting Formula One racing qualifying sessions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] During the first phase of qualifying, if the circuit is dry, any driver who is eliminated in the first qualifying session and fails to set a lap within 107% of the fastest time in that session will not be allowed to start the race without permission from the race stewards.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] For example, if the fastest Q1 lap time was 100 seconds, each driver who is eliminated in the session must complete at least one lap within 107 seconds to guarantee a race start.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule was introduced for the 1996 season and remained in force until 2002.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] It was reintroduced for the 2011 season with minor modifications due to the knock-out qualifying format.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The governing body of F1, the Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile (FIA), introduced the 107% rule at a meeting of its World Motor Sport Council in June 1995, immediately prior to the French Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] This followed a recommendation from the Formula One Commission, a working group of F1 representatives, to introduce such a measure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Over the previous few years, the number of entries per season had dropped to 26, the maximum threshold for race starters, allowing every entrant to qualify for the race regardless of speed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] For 1995, new technical regulations spaced out the field, whilst numerous teams with comparatively small budgets and slow cars, such as Forti, Pacific, and Simtek, were competing in the sport.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The regulation was originally planned to come into effect from the 1995 Hungarian Grand Prix, but this required unanimous support amongst the teams, and was vetoed by Forti and Pacific.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Nevertheless, the fact that it was supported by the majority of the teams allowed the 107% rule's introduction from the start of the 1996 season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The mid-1990s also brought a number of pay drivers to the sport whose speeds would not have allowed them to race, such as Giovanni Lavaggi and Jean-Denis Delétraz.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Commenting on the introduction of the 107% rule, FIA President Max Mosley said that "any small team which is properly organised will be able to get within the 107 per cent margin".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The sport's commercial rights holder, Bernie Ecclestone, agreed with this sentiment, saying in an interview that "Formula 1 is the best.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] On the other hand, the smaller teams were concerned at the prospect of having to lap within a maximum time in order to qualify, which they saw as exacerbating the inequalities already existent within the sport.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Pacific's commercial manager, Mark Gallagher, said: "We have to say the 107% rule gives rise to concern among teams without works engines.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] It's got more to do with engines than chassis, and that's an area outside our direct capability.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Closing the gap to Minardi is quite feasible, but the sudden arrival of the rule is worrying.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule was thus introduced at the 1996 Australian Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] It was breached immediately, as Forti drivers Luca Badoer and Andrea Montermini failed to lap within 107% of Jacques Villeneuve's pole position time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] This had been an expected outcome, as the team was using an upgraded version of the previous year's Forti FG01 chassis, which had only qualified within 107% of pole position on one of thirty-four occasions beforehand.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Both drivers also failed to qualify for the European Grand Prix, the fourth round of the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the following race, the San Marino Grand Prix, Badoer drove the more competitive FG03 chassis for the first time, whilst Montermini failed to make the 107% cut in the older car.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Both then failed to qualify for the Spanish Grand Prix two races later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] By the tenth round of the championship, the British Grand Prix, the team was running out of money and made only a token attempt to qualify after not taking part in the preceding free practice sessions, neither car making the time limit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Following the next race, in which the team did not complete any laps at all, Forti withdrew from Formula One.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In the latter half of the season, the Minardi team replaced regular driver Giancarlo Fisichella with the paying Giovanni Lavaggi, who failed to make the 107% cut at the German, Belgian, and Japanese Grands Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In 1997, the 107% rule was only invoked at the season-opening Australian Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Villeneuve again set pole position with a time over a second faster than his nearest rival, resulting in a well-spaced field.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] As a result, Pedro Diniz, Vincenzo Sospiri, and Ricardo Rosset all failed to make the 107% mark.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Diniz was allowed to race at the discretion of the race stewards, who judged him capable of lapping within the limit, as he had indeed done so during the free practice session prior to qualifying.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The FIA cited "exceptional circumstances" as the reason for his failure to do so during the qualifying session itself.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Sospiri and Rosset, driving for the new MasterCard Lola team, were five and six seconds off Diniz's time respectively, and well outside the qualification limit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Neither driver was allowed to start the race, and the team folded before the next Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] During the 1998 season, Rosset—now driving for the Tyrrell team—failed to qualify on five occasions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] He lapped outside the 107% time during qualifying sessions for the Spanish, Monaco, Hungarian, and Japanese Grands Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] He also failed to qualify for the German Grand Prix, but this was due to him not completing any laps at all after injuring his right elbow as a result of a heavy crash during free practice.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule was invoked on two occasions in 1999.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the first round of the championship—the Australian Grand Prix—Marc Gené failed to lap within the required percentage of the pole position time in his Minardi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] As with Diniz two years earlier, he was given dispensation to race after lapping within the limit during the free practice sessions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the French Grand Prix later in the season, a qualifying session marked by a varying intensity of rainfall saw five drivers—Damon Hill, Gené, Luca Badoer, Pedro de la Rosa, and Toranosuke Takagi—miss the cut-off, but all were allowed to start the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] After a 2000 season in which no driver transgressed the 107% rule, it was enforced on three occasions in 2001.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the opening race in Australia, Tarso Marques failed to lap within the required time for Minardi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] He was given permission to race under the reason of "exceptional circumstances", but this was despite the fact that he had not managed to set a time within the 107% mark in any session all weekend.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] It was rumoured that Marques was allowed to race because the team had been bought prior to the start of the season by Australian Paul Stoddart, who wanted both cars to compete in Minardi's new "home" Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the British Grand Prix, Marques again fell foul of the regulation, but was not allowed to start on this occasion.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The Belgian Grand Prix also witnessed a wet qualifying session in which the track steadily dried, resulting in the four slowest qualifiers—Jos Verstappen, Fernando Alonso, Enrique Bernoldi, and Marques—failing to lap within 107% of pole position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] As in the similar case of the French Grand Prix two years previously, all were allowed to start the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule also came into effect during the 2002 season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the first round of the championship, the Australian Grand Prix, Takuma Sato crashed heavily during free practice and had to use the Jordan team's spare car for qualifying, only for the replacement to stop with a gearbox problem without setting a time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] By the time his teammate, Fisichella, did his first run and handed over his own chassis, it had begun to rain, leaving Sato with no chance of making the required time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] However, he was allowed to start the race as in the case of previous cases affected by changeable weather conditions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Minardi driver Alex Yoong failed to qualify for the San Marino, British, and German Grands Prix under the conditions of the rule, a turn of events which led to his replacement by Anthony Davidson for two races.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the French Grand Prix, the Arrows team was running out of money and made a token appearance during the qualifying session to avoid FIA-imposed fines for missing rounds of the championship; drivers Heinz-Harald Frentzen and Bernoldi failed to lap within the required time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Frentzen subsequently left the circuit with ten minutes of the session still remaining, making the team's ploy obvious.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Fisichella also failed to qualify as he did not set a time during this session, although this was the result of his withdrawal from the event following a heavy crash during free practice.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In total, there were 37 cases in which the 107% rule was broken during the period in which it was a Formula One Sporting Regulation.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Of these, 13 drivers were allowed to start the relevant race due to "exceptional circumstances".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The rule affected 23 out of the 116 Grands Prix in which it applied.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The qualifying system changed for the 2003 season with the introduction of two ordered single-lap sessions to replace the previous free hour-long session in which drivers were allowed to complete twelve laps.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Drivers also had to qualify with the race fuel on board their cars.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Due to the scope for greater time disparities throughout the field that could occur as a result, the 107% rule was not mentioned when the FIA finalised the format prior to the beginning of the season, despite an earlier assurance that the rule would still apply.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The governing body subsequently proposed the formal cancellation of the rule, which ceased to apply with effect from the 2002 Japanese Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Following the 2003 season, the timing of the two single-lap sessions was altered for them to occur on the same day, within 15 minutes of each other.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] During the 2004 season, the system's flaws were exposed, and proposed changes to the qualifying system made midway through the championship at one point seemed to suggest that the 107% rule would return as part of a new format.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In the end, however, only minor changes relating to the timing of the existing sessions were made.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Minardi team owner Paul Stoddart was particularly opposed to the reintroduction of the rule.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the start of the 2010 season, new FIA President Jean Todt said that he was in favour of re-introducing the 107% rule, as the qualifying system had changed again so that all of the sessions were carried out with low fuel levels.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] On 23 June, a meeting of the FIA World Motor Sport Council determined that the 107% rule would be reintroduced for the 2011 season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The rule applies only to the first of the three qualifying sessions for each race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] From its re-introduction to the end of the 2015 season, the 107% rule was broken a further 17 times at 12 different races, all but one by HRT, Caterham, and Virgin/Marussia drivers.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Unlike the rule's first period of application, where infringing drivers were very rarely allowed to compete, only four of these occurrences of rule violation resulted in the drivers being barred from the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] These were Vitantonio Liuzzi and Narain Karthikeyan at the 2011 Australian Grand Prix, and Pedro de la Rosa and Karthikeyan at the 2012 Australian Grand Prix – all of whom drove for HRT.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the 2016 Hungarian Grand Prix, eleven drivers failed to reach the 107% limit as the session was stopped for inclement weather and subsequent incidents, but all were permitted to compete.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Beginning with the 2018 season, the regulations were amended so that the 107% rule would not be enforced if the track was declared wet by the race director during qualifying.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule, or variations thereof, has also been used in other motorsport series.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Formula E applies an alternative 110% rule in qualifying.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Race stewards have discretion to allow drivers who broke the rule to partake in the race, usually by looking at the times posted in free practice sessions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The rule is most commonly broken when a driver fails to enter his qualifying lap in time or has had his qualifying lap invalidated (therefore only his entry lap is recorded).
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The car breaking down or a crash during the session could also lead to a violation of this rule.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] There has been no occasion where a driver was not allowed to compete in the race so far.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule is also used in the GP2 Series as well as its successor Formula 2, where it has been applied on four occasions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Marcos Martínez failed to qualify for his debut race meeting at the Hungaroring in 2007 after failing to set a lap time due to engine problems, despite lapping within 107% of the fastest time in free practice.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] At the Monaco round of the 2009 season, Ricardo Teixeira failed to lap within 107% of the pole position time and was not allowed to take part in the races.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Perera also failed to qualify for the Spa-Francorchamps races under the 107% criteria.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Alessio Deledda became the first driver since Perera in this racing category to fall victim to the 107% rule.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] He qualified 6.341 seconds off from the fastest time set by Robert Shwartzman in his group during qualifying for the Monaco Grand Prix round in 2021.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] As he was 7.314 seconds off the fastest time set by Shwartzman during the practice session, he was unable to take part in all three races in the weekend.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] He was, however, given permission to start by the stewards, after it was later revealed after the weekend that Deledda's car had mechanical problems and that he was within the 107% time during the previous round at Bahrain.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The 107% rule is also used in the GP3 Series and the succeeding Formula 3.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] So far, the rule has only been in effect on one occasion during the GP3 era.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In the 2012 Silverstone round, Carmen Jordá failed to set a lap time within 107% of the pole time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] As she was also outside 107% of the fastest time in the practice session, she was not allowed to start the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] MotoGP uses a similar rule for race competition, where riders must be within 105% of the lap times of the fastest rider in each of the practice sessions in order to take part in qualifying sessions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Between 2013 and 2021, the 107% rule was also used in the competition.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Riders including Aleix Espargaro and Cal Crutchlow criticized about the effectiveness of the rule when Christophe Ponsson finished one lap slower than the race winner in 2018 San Marino Grand Prix, urging the FIM to tighten the rule.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Japanese rider Takumi Takahashi, who won Suzuka 8 Hours in 2010, failed to qualify in 2023 San Marino motorcycle Grand Prix after running 0.6 slower than the 105% of the fastest lap time in practice sessions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The IndyCar Series uses a similar rule for race competition, where cars must be within 105% of the lap times of the fastest car.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] NASCAR uses a similar rule for race competition, where cars must be within 115% of the fastest lap set in the final practice.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In Super GT series, a slightly different 107% rule is being used.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Until 2024, the base time is calculated by the mean time of top three cars within a class rather than the fastest lap time by a single car in that class.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] All drivers in the non-seeded teams must set a lap time within this time in order to qualify for the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] However, teams which could not qualify in official qualifying sessions may still be allowed to retry in following day's practice session, providing reasons such as accidents.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In this case, the 107% of top three cars in practice session's will be used instead, in return, teams will start at the back of the grid.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In races using the knockout format, a separate qualifying session will be launched prior the knockout qualifying to decide teams which are allowed to take part in the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] From 2024, this was removed from Q1 lap times and only applied to Q2 laps.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] Another major difference of the 107% rule in Super GT is that there is a protection system called "seeded teams", which is awarded to each team which participated in all races and finished within the top 12 of its class in the previous season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] These teams, provided they meet other entrance requirements, are allowed to participate in all races even when they fail to meet the qualifying time in official qualifying sessions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] A team's "seeded team" status is forfeited when the team switches class or withdraws from the series, and the void caused by this will not be filled in by other teams.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] The World Rally-Raid Championship used a 107% rule to set the starting lineup for the first stage of a given rally.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] If a driver regardless of category set a time within 107% of the prologue's winner, they were to start ahead of those with slower times for the next day.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] This percentage expanded to 115% for drivers with a gold or platinum FIA Driver Categorisation.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/107-rule] In mid-2026, the percentage was increased to 117%.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] , finished the season in second, three points behind Fittipaldi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The **1974 Formula One season** was the 28th season of FIA Formula One motor racing.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] It featured the 1974 World Championship of F1 Drivers and the 1974 International Cup for F1 Manufacturers, contested concurrently over a fifteen-race series which commenced on 13 January and ended on 6 October.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The season also included three non-championship races.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Defending champion Jackie Stewart did not drive in 1974, having announced his retirement at the end of the previous season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] South African Jody Scheckter finished third for Tyrrell Racing after having an outside chance of also becoming champion.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi's triumph with the British manufacturer wrought many firsts for Formula One and served as a precursor to what was to come; it was the first title for the McLaren team and the first of many titles for a team sponsored by the Marlboro cigarette brand.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Two F1 drivers died over the course of the season: Peter Revson during practice for the South African Grand Prix and Helmut Koinigg during the United States Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The following teams and drivers contested the 1974 World Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Selfseal breakaway fuel couplings were mandated to reduce the chance of a fire in accidents.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] In qualifying for the opening round in Argentina, Ronnie Peterson took pole in his Lotus ahead of Clay Regazzoni's Ferrari and Emerson Fittipaldi's McLaren.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Peterson led at the start, whereas fellow front-row starter Regazzoni spun, causing chaos.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi was hit by teammate Mike Hailwood and lost two laps while repairing his car, and James Hunt inherited second whereas Peter Revson, who started fourth, retired in the chaos.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Hunt spun before the first lap was over, and second place went to Carlos Reutemann's Brabham.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann passed Peterson on the third lap, and soon the Swede began to fade badly with brake problems.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] As a result, Mike Hailwood and Denny Hulme in their McLarens were second and third, ahead of Jacky Ickx and Niki Lauda in the second Lotus and Ferrari.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Hulme, Ickx and Lauda all passed Hailwood and then Ickx suffered a puncture mid-race and had to pit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni was recovering from his spin, and passed Hailwood soon after.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann continued to lead until his engine began to misfire, with Hulme closing in and taking the lead on the penultimate lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Hulme went on to win, with Lauda and Regazzoni completing the podium after Reutemann ran out of fuel on the last lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi took a popular home pole in Brazil, beating Reutemann and Lauda.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann, eager to make up after his bad luck in Argentina, took the lead at the start, with Peterson up to second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann led early on, but was passed by both Peterson and Fittipaldi on lap 4.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Peterson battled with former Lotus teammate Fittipaldi for the next 12 laps, until he suffered a slow puncture.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi passed him and took the lead, whereas Peterson dropped backwards.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi went on to take a home victory, with Regazzoni getting second and Ickx third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The field went to South Africa after a two-month break.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda took pole position, with Carlos Pace's Surtees also on the front row.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Arturo Merzario in the Iso-Marlboro team was an amazing third on the grid.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] At the start, Lauda took the lead, whereas surprise packages Pace and Merzario were soon swamped by the field.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann was up to second, and he took the lead from Lauda on the tenth lap, and he would remain ahead for the rest of the afternoon.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni was third ahead of Fittipaldi and Hailwood, but soon Jean-Pierre Beltoise's BRM soon passed the two McLarens, as Fittipaldi began to drop back.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda and Regazzoni both retired very late in the race when their engines blew up, and thus Beltoise and Hailwood completed the podium behind Reutemann.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The first European round of the championship was in Spain, and it was Lauda who took pole ahead of Peterson and Regazzoni.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] On race day, the track was wet but drying, and Peterson was able to beat Lauda off the line.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The Lotuses and the Ferraris battled until Peterson's engine failed and Ickx lost a wheel which was not fastened properly after the stop for slicks.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] This left Lauda to take his first career win, and Regazzoni to complete a Ferrari 1–2, with Fittipaldi third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The next race was in Belgium, and Regazzoni continued Ferrari's streak of poles, and Jody Scheckter's Tyrrell taking second with Lauda third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni led in the early stages, with Fittipaldi climbing up to second in the first lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Later, Lauda passed Scheckter for third, and this became second when Regazzoni went to the grass after an incident with a backmarker.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi thus won the race, from Lauda, with Scheckter third after Regazzoni suffered fuel feed problems on the last lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] In the streets of Monaco, Lauda and Regazzoni took the front row for Ferrari, with Peterson's Lotus behind them in third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The Ferraris motored away, with Regazzoni leading after beating his teammate off the line, with Peterson down in sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni led until he made a mistake and spun off, rejoining fifth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda was now leading Jean-Pierre Jarier's Shadow, Peterson and Scheckter.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Peterson disposed of Jarier, and took the lead when Lauda's engine blew up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Peterson went on to win, with Scheckter taking second from Jarier.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The Tyrrells were dominant in qualifying, with Patrick Depailler taking the pole from Jody Scheckter, with the Ferraris of Lauda and Regazzoni on the second row.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Scheckter passed his teammate to take the lead at the start, with Peterson gaining three places to jump up to second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] It was all to no avail, because he retired in the opening laps with a driveshaft failure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The Tyrrells were now up front, with the Ferraris behind them.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The gearboxes of both Ferraris failed and both retired, promoting James Hunt in the Hesketh to third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Scheckter duly won, with Depailler completing a dominant 1–2 for Tyrrell, with Hunt third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The Netherlands was host to the eighth round, and Lauda took his fourth pole of the year, with teammate Regazzoni alongside, and the McLarens of Fittipaldi and Hailwood next up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda led from the start, will Hailwood jumping up to second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] But Regazzoni took only two laps to regain second, and Hailwood was soon passed by Depailler and Fittipaldi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Depailler held third until he struggled with oversteer, and so Fittipaldi was through.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda won, with Regazzoni making it a 1–2 for Ferrari, with Fittipaldi getting third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda took pole again in France, with Peterson in second, and Tom Pryce in the Shadow a surprising third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda and Peterson maintained their positions at the start, whereas Pryce collided with Hunt and Carlos Reutemann, with all three retiring as Regazzoni took third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda and Peterson battled it out in the early stages, but soon Lauda began to suffer from a vibration and Peterson was able to pass him and pull away.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Peterson went on to win, with Lauda managing second, and Regazzoni third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Great Britain was host to the tenth round of the championship, and Lauda surprised no one by taking pole, with Peterson again alongside and Scheckter third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] At the start, Lauda led, whereas Peterson dropped behind Scheckter and Regazzoni.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The order of Lauda, Scheckter, Regazzoni and Peterson remained unchanged for the first half of the race until Regazzoni and Peterson had to pit for new tyres after running over debris.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Late in the race, leader Lauda suffered a puncture, and the lead went to Scheckter.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Scheckter duly won, with Fittipaldi getting second and Jacky Ickx third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] As a result, with exactly two-thirds of the championship gone, the championship was an extremely close four-way battle.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda led with 38 points, but he was only a point ahead of Fittipaldi, with Regazzoni and Scheckter lurking three points behind.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The third part of the championship started in Germany at the 14.2 mile (22.8 km) Nürburgring circuit, and Lauda took pole as usual, and Regazzoni ensured that Ferrari locked out the front row, with other contenders Fittipaldi third and Scheckter fourth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni took the lead at the start, whereas Lauda and Scheckter collided on the first lap at the Nord Kurve with the former retiring, and the latter continuing unscathed in second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi suffered a puncture and had to pit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni went on to win and take the championship lead, with Scheckter second and Reutemann third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda took his eighth pole position of the championship, and fifth consecutive, in his home round in Austria with Reutemann and Fittipaldi second and third on the grid.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann got the better of Lauda at the start, with Regazzoni fourth behind the second Brabham of Carlos Pace, and Fittipaldi down to seventh behind Scheckter.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Scheckter retired with a blown engine, whereas Regazzoni soon passed Pace.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda soon dropped down the order with a misfiring engine and soon retired.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni was second, and Fittipaldi was third after passing Pace.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi's engine also blew up, and Regazzoni dropped back and ultimately had to bit with a slow puncture.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann took the victory, with Denny Hulme second and James Hunt third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Regazzoni recovered to finish fifth and get two points, whereas his other rivals scored none.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The Ferrari fans were happy to see Lauda take pole for the Italian GP, with the Brabhams of Reutemann and Pace following him on the grid.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The start did not change the positions, with Lauda leading Reutemann and Pace.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Soon, Regazzoni passed both the Brabhams to and then Reutemann retired with a gearbox failure and Pace had to pit with tyre troubles.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] This left Lauda leading Regazzoni for the perfect Ferrari 1–2, a long way ahead of third-placed Peterson.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] That was not to last as Lauda retired with a water leak, handing the lead to Regazzoni but Regazzoni's engine failed 10 laps later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Peterson took the lead and won, holding off Fittipaldi and Scheckter finished third to close up the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The penultimate round of the championship was in Canada, and Fittipaldi took pole, just beating Lauda with Scheckter third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda took Fittipaldi off the line and led, with Regazzoni up to third ahead of Scheckter, but Scheckter retook the position on the second lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The four contenders were occupying the first four spots – Lauda leading Fittipaldi, Scheckter and Regazzoni.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] But Scheckter crashed after suffering a brake failure, and then Lauda crashed out late in the race after running over debris, ending his championship hopes.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Fittipaldi won the race from Regazzoni, with Peterson completing the podium.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] This meant that Fittipaldi and Regazzoni were level on points into the last race, with Scheckter the outsider seven points behind.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The championship decider was to be held at the United States.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann took pole with Hunt alongside on the front row, with home hero Mario Andretti third in a Parnelli.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Scheckter was sixth, whereas Fittipaldi and Regazzoni were eighth and ninth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Reutemann converted his pole to a lead at the start, with Hunt second and Pace third after Andretti stalled.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Behind Lauda was Scheckter, Fittipaldi and Regazzoni running together.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The front three quickly pulled away, as Lauda held up Scheckter and Fittipaldi in an attempt to help Regazzoni.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] However, Regazzoni was struggling with handling problems and dropping back down the field.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] He pitted for tyres twice but found it to be no avail, and he was two laps down.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Lauda and Scheckter both retired in the latter half of the race, promoting Fittipaldi to fourth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Pace took second from Hunt with four laps left, as the Englishman was suffering from fading brakes.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The race was won by Reutemann, with Pace ensuring that Brabham cap off the season with a 1–2, and Hunt was third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Emerson Fittipaldi finished fourth to ensure that he was the World Champion, beating Regazzoni by three points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The race was marred by the death of young Austrian Helmut Koinigg when his car crashed into the wall after a puncture on the 10th lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The barrier which the car hit split on impact, and Koinigg was decapitated.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Points were awarded to the top six classified finishers.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The International Cup for F1 Manufacturers only counted the points of the highest-finishing driver for each race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] For both the Championship and the Cup, the best seven results from rounds 1-8 and the best six results from rounds 9-15 were counted.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Numbers without parentheses are championship points; numbers in parentheses are total points scored.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The FIA did not award a championship classification to drivers who did not score championship points and did not apply a classification tiebreaker system to drivers gaining an equal number of championship points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Race results shown in **Bold** in the above table indicate that points were awarded and retained.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Race results shown within brackets indicate that points were awarded but not retained.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The FIA did not award a championship classification to a manufacturer that did not score championship points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] The following races were open to Formula One cars, but did not count towards the World Championship of F1 Drivers or the International Cup for F1 Manufacturers.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] *"Safety Improvements in F1 since 1963".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Archived from the original on 24 September 2019.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1974-formula-one-season] Only the best 7 results from the first 8 races and the best 6 results from the last 7 races counted towards the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] (pictured in 1977) posthumously finished in second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The **1978 Formula One season** was the 32nd season of FIA Formula One motor racing.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] It featured the 1978 World Championship of F1 Drivers and the International Cup for F1 Constructors, contested concurrently over a sixteen race series which commenced on 15 January and ended on 8 October.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The season also included the non-championship BRDC International Trophy.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Mario Andretti won the Drivers' World Championship, driving for JPS-Lotus.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] He remains the last American driver to win the World Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] His victory at the Dutch Grand Prix is also the last for an American driver.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Ronnie Peterson was awarded second place in the Drivers' standings posthumously, having died from medical complications after an accident at Monza during the Italian Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Lotus won the International Cup for F1 Constructors, for the last time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Championship defendants Niki Lauda and Ferrari had parted ways late in 1977, and both parties struggled to repeat the successes they had enjoyed the previous seasons.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Carlos Reutemann finished third in the championship in the lead Ferrari, while Lauda finished fourth with Brabham.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Apart from Peterson's death, the year saw another tragedy when Peterson's Swedish compatriot Gunnar Nilsson died from cancer, having been forced to cut his career short after the previous season because of the disease.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The following drivers and constructors contested the 1978 World Championship of F1 Drivers and the International Cup for F1 Constructors.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The 1978 World Championship of F1 Drivers and the International Cup for F1 Constructors were contested concurrently over a sixteen-race series.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The 1978 season started at the varied Parque Almirante Brown circuit in Buenos Aires, Argentina, where Mario Andretti took pole in his Lotus, with home favourite Carlos Reutemann's Ferrari joining him on the front row and Ronnie Peterson in the other Lotus third on the grid.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The start was uneventful, with Andretti and Reutemann easily keeping first and second, with John Watson in the Brabham taking third from Peterson.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Watson took second from Reutemann on the seventh lap, but Andretti was uncatchable.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Reutemann ran third for a while but then began to drop down the order due to tire problems, so reigning world champion Niki Lauda took third in his Brabham, which became second with ten laps left when Watson's engine blew up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti motored on to a crushing victory, with Lauda second and Patrick Depailler's Tyrrell taking the final spot on the podium.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This had been an unusual Argentine Grand Prix- although the summer weather had been usually hot (although not as hot as the previous year), the attrition rate hadn't been as high, nor had the polesitter retired.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Brazil was the country where the drivers traveled for the second round of the season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Formula One made its first visit to the new Jacarepagua Autodrome in Rio de Janeiro, after six years at the very bumpy and demanding Interlagos circuit in São Paulo – the Jacarepagua circuit was to be visited by Formula One for the rest of the next decade.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The typically extreme weather during January in Rio meant that this race was run in oppressively hot and humid conditions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Peterson took pole with James Hunt driving for McLaren beating Andretti to second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] At the start, Reutemann beat the trio into the first corner, with Hunt and Andretti following, as Peterson got a bad start.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Hunt ran second until he had to pit for tyres, as a result, Andretti took the place until late in the race when he suffered gearbox issues, which handed second to Fittipaldi and third to Lauda.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Hunt eventually spun out of the race after being caught out by the hot and humid conditions on lap 26, as did Tambay on lap 35 and Villeneuve one lap later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] After a long break, the season resumed at the Kyalami circuit in South Africa for the 300th World Championship Grand Prix, where defending champion Lauda took his first pole for Brabham with Andretti alongside and Hunt next.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti took the lead at the start, and set about building a gap, whereas Lauda dropped behind Jody Scheckter's Wolf.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Young Italian Riccardo Patrese was on a charge in the Arrows, passing Lauda for third after 20 laps.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] As the race continued, both Andretti and Scheckter began to suffer from tyre issues and were passed by Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Depailler was up to second ahead of Lauda, but the latter's engine failed, handing third to Andretti.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Patrese, however, seemed to have the race in his pocket until his engine failed, and Depailler took the lead, but his Tyrrell began to trail smoke.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti was up to second, but he had to pit for fuel, and thus his teammate Peterson took the place before catching and passing Depailler on the last lap to win after some wheel-banging.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The next race was in the famous Long Beach circuit near Los Angeles in the American state of California.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The Ferraris dominated qualifying, with Reutemann taking pole ahead of teammate Gilles Villeneuve, with defending champion Lauda and home hero Andretti on the second row.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] When the race started, Watson in fifth late-braked all into turn one, though he ran wide and Villeneuve took the lead, whereas Reutemann dropped down to fourth behind Lauda.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The Ferraris, with the two Brabhams in between, ran together until Watson's engine failed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Alan Jones's Williams was up to fourth and closed in on the now lead trio, which became a duo when Lauda went out with an electrical failure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Villeneuve and Reutemann ran 1–2, with Jones putting both under pressure before Villeneuve also retired after colliding with a backmarker.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Jones suffered from fuel pressure problems and began to drop back, handing second to Andretti, to the fans' delight.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The rest of the race passed without incident, and with all challengers out of contention, Reutemann won comfortably ahead of Andretti and Depailler.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Round Five took place in Monaco after an extended gap once the Japanese Grand Prix at the Suzuka circuit was cancelled.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Once again, Reutemann started on pole with the Brabham duo of Watson and Lauda second and third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Watson had a good start and led into the first corner, whereas Reutemann collided with Hunt and had to pit for repairs, which left Depailler and Lauda second and third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] For the first half of the race, the top three remained the same until Watson had an off allowing Depailler and Lauda through, but the latter then suffered a puncture and had to pit for tyres before charging back up and retaking second from Watson towards the end of the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] At the front, Depailler took his first career victory, with Lauda second and Scheckter third after Watson made another mistake in the final laps.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The main news before the Belgian GP at Zolder was that the new Lotus 79 was ready to race, and immediately Andretti showed its pace by taking pole comfortably from Reutemann and Lauda.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] He converted it to a first-corner lead, whereas Reutemann had a bad start and got swamped by the field, causing a chain reaction in which Lauda was hit by Scheckter and had to retire.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This left Villeneuve second and Peterson third, but neither could keep pace with Andretti, who was able to drive away.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The first 40 laps went without incident until Villeneuve suffered a puncture and had to pit, which dropped him back down to fifth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] A few laps later, Peterson also pitted for new tyres leaving the charging Reutemann second ahead of Jacques Laffite's Ligier.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Peterson, on the new tyres, was much quicker and could pass them both in the closing stages, and Laffite attempted to pass Reutemann on the last lap, but they collided, and Laffite was out.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti cruised to an untroubled victory, with Peterson making it a Lotus 1–2 and Reutemann completing the podium.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The next race was at the tight, twisty Jarama circuit near Madrid in Spain.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Once again, the new Lotus 79 demonstrated its speed, with Andretti on pole again with Peterson alongside, and Reutemann had to settle for the second row.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] It was Hunt who got a great start and led into the first corner from Andretti and Reutemann, with Peterson dropping back to ninth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Hunt led for seven laps before Andretti passed him and pulled away.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Reutemann ran third until he had to pit for tyres, so Watson inherited third until Laffite passed him, but soon the recovering Peterson passed both of them.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Hunt now suffered from tyre problems, and he also began to drop back, and so Peterson was able to take second and Laffite third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] That was how it ended: Andretti won over Peterson in another Lotus 1–2, and Laffite got the final spot on the podium.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Before the Swedish GP at the isolated Anderstorp circuit, the Brabham team had developed a new "fan car" much to the anger of the other teams, but the FIA allowed it to race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] However, it did not stop Andretti from continuing his pole run, but it got Watson to qualify second and Lauda third- while running on full fuel tanks.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] When the race started, Andretti led into the first corner, with Lauda getting second from his teammate.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Riccardo Patrese got up to third in his Arrows until home driver Peterson passed him, but by then, Andretti and Lauda had escaped.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Peterson struggled with a slow puncture, whereas Andretti and Lauda battled, with Andretti making a mistake just after mid-distance, allowing Lauda to take the lead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Lauda went on to win the race, his first for Brabham after Andretti's challenge ended due to an engine failure, which left Patrese and Peterson to take second and third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This was the last Swedish Grand Prix to date-with the deaths of Ronnie Peterson and Gunnar Nilsson, Swedish interest faded in Formula One, and there was no money for the race to be held.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Brabham was forced to revert to their previous car, but it did not deter them, with Watson on pole and Lauda starting third behind Andretti.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] At the start, Watson led into the first corner, with Andretti following and Patrick Tambay putting his McLaren in third, but that order did not remain for long as Andretti took the lead from Watson on the first lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Lauda and Peterson were also on the move as they passed Watson and Tambay to jump into second and third, but Lauda suffered another engine failure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This left the two Lotus cars running 1–2, and they finished like that, with Andretti taking his third win in four races, and the podium was completed by Hunt, who passed Watson mid-race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The field went to Britain for the next round, and this time it was Peterson who beat Andretti to pole, as Lotus took the front row, with Scheckter next up on the second row.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti took the lead at the start from Peterson, and the two Lotus cars quickly pulled out a gap until Peterson retired with an engine failure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti had a big lead to Scheckter and continued to extend it until he had to pit with a puncture, and he eventually retired when his engine also failed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Scheckter inherited the lead, but Lauda put him under pressure and took the lead before Scheckter went out with gearbox problems.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This put Reutemann up to second, closing down and passing Lauda in the late stages of the race to win.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Lauda had to settle for second, and his teammate Watson took a podium in his home race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The West German race was next on the calendar, and there were no surprises in qualifying, with Andretti on pole and Peterson alongside him, with Lauda third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] At the start, Peterson got off better and took the lead from Andretti, but he held it for only four laps before Andretti retook it.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Lauda ran third in the early stages, but Alan Jones passed him, and the duo battled until Lauda's engine failed yet again.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The two Lotus cars were cruising at the front, and Jones ran third comfortably until he retired with a fuel vaporization problem.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Lotus's hopes of a 1–2 ended when Peterson's gearbox failed, but Andretti was unaffected by that and cruised to his fifth win of the season, with Scheckter second and Laffite third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The crowds for the Austrian GP were full of Lauda fans; however, for them, Lauda qualified only 12th as the Lotus cars again took the front row, with Peterson on pole.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The surprise in qualifying was Jean-Pierre Jabouille, who qualified his turbocharged Renault third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The start saw Peterson lead into the first corner, with Reutemann snatching second from Andretti.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti tried to get the place back later in the lap, but the two collided, and Andretti retired after his car spun into the barriers while Reutemann lost a couple of places to Patrick Depailler and Scheckter.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] On the fourth lap, a heavy rainshower hit the track, and Reutemann spun off and was beached, but the marshals push-started his car as it was in a dangerous position, while Scheckter crashed out, and the race was stopped.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The race restarted after the rain relented, and once again, Peterson led, followed by Depailler and Lauda.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] As the track began to dry, Peterson started to pull away, and behind, Reutemann was on a charge and passed Lauda for third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Still, he was black-flagged for receiving outside assistance, and Lauda crashed out soon after, leaving Gilles Villeneuve third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The drivers changed to slicks, but the top 3 remained the same until the end; Peterson won ahead of Depailler, with Villeneuve taking his first-ever podium.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The drivers went to the Netherlands for the next race, qualifying as expected, Andretti taking pole with Peterson alongside in the all-Lotus front row and Lauda heading the second row.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] At the start, Andretti led with Peterson following, whereas Jacques Laffite challenged Lauda.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The Lotus cars quickly built up a good gap, while Laffite challenged Lauda early on but then began to drop down the order with tyre issues.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The race was relatively uneventful, and Andretti went to take victory, with Peterson completing another Lotus 1–2, leaving Lauda to take third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The Italian race was host to round fourteen, and as usual, Andretti took pole with Gilles Villeneuve pleasing the Ferrari fans by qualifying second, ahead of Jabouille's turbocharged Renault.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] When the race started, Andretti and Villeneuve got away comfortably, with Lauda and Jabouille following, but the rest of the field was bunched up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Riccardo Patrese's Arrows overtook many of the cars on the right-hand side of the circuit next to the pitlane since he got a rolling start when the starter Gianni Restelli started the race prematurely.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] He rejoined the other cars just in front of the blocked entrance to the old Monza banking, and James Hunt got so surprised that he veered left and hit Peterson's Lotus 78 with his left front wheel.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Peterson spun right and rammed the right Armco barrier hard, head-on; the front end of his Lotus 78 was crushed during the impact.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Seven other drivers were collected: Carlos Reutemann, Hans Joachim Stuck, Patrick Depailler, Didier Pironi, Vittorio Brambilla, and Clay Regazzoni.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Peterson's car broke in two on impact with the barriers and caught fire, and Vittorio Brambilla, who was in the Surtees, was hit on the head by a flying wheel.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Peterson and Brambilla were taken to hospital, the former with 27 fractures in his legs and feet, and there was a concern for the latter who was unconscious after being hit by the wheel.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The rest of the drivers were uninjured, and most of them were able to take the restart.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The race restarted almost four hours after the original start.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Again there was confusion as the front-row starters Andretti and Villeneuve went too early, but the rest of the field did not follow, and both Andretti and Villeneuve were handed one-minute penalties as a result.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] On the track, Villeneuve led ahead of Andretti and Jabouille until Jabouille retired, handing third place on the track to Lauda.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] His teammate Watson battled with Reutemann and Laffite and eventually pulled away.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The battle on the track was between Villeneuve and Andretti, with the Lotus driver passing Villeneuve with five laps left.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti crossed the line first, with Villeneuve close behind, but when their one-minute penalties were added, Lauda emerged the victor ahead of Watson and Reutemann.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] In a hospital, Peterson had a clot forming in his bloodstream after an operation on his legs, slipped into a coma overnight, and died the following day.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This made Andretti the world champion, although he did not celebrate it, and mourned for Peterson along with his fellow drivers.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Brambilla was able to recover from his injuries.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The season's penultimate round was at Watkins Glen in the United States, and Lotus had hired Jean-Pierre Jarier to replace Peterson.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Patrese could not race because the Grand Prix Drivers Association had deemed him responsible for the accident, ultimately killing Peterson.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] New World Champion, and home hero, Andretti was shaken up more than most drivers due to Peterson's death, but it did not stop him from romping to pole ahead of Reutemann, with Alan Jones's Williams heading the second row.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti kept the lead at the start, with Reutemann and Villeneuve following ahead of Jones.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Andretti suffered from an ill-handling car that had brake troubles and was soon passed by Reutemann, Villeneuve, and later Jones.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Reutemann and Villeneuve ran 1–2 for Ferrari until Villeneuve's engine blew up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This left Jones second and Andretti third, but Andretti's engine blew up, handing third to Lauda until he also suffered the same fate, thus leaving Scheckter third before a charging Jarier passed him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] However, Jarier ran out of fuel with four laps left, giving the place back to Scheckter.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Reutemann took a comfortable win from Jones, with Scheckter completing the podium.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The season finished in Canada, coming to the new île Notre-Dame circuit in Montreal; the Formula One circus left the previous Canadian GP location of Mosport Park due to safety issues with the Toronto circuit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] In qualifying, Jarier starred by qualifying on pole ahead of Scheckter and home hero Villeneuve.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Jarier could easily lead into the first corner, with Jones jumping up to second after a brilliant start and dropping Scheckter down to third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] As Jarier began to pull away, Jones suffered a slow puncture and fell down the field as the race progressed, promoting Scheckter to second and Villeneuve to third, and then Villeneuve passed Scheckter mid-race to take second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Jarier continued to dominate until he retired with an oil leak, leaving Villeneuve to take his first career win in his home race ahead of Scheckter, with Reutemann taking third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The International Cup for F1 Constructors only counted the points of the highest-finishing driver for each race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] For both the Championship and the Cup, the best seven results from rounds 1-8 and the best seven results from rounds 9-16 were counted.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] Official FIA results for the 1978 International Cup for F1 Constructors listed the positions as (1) JPS-Lotus (2) Ferrari (3) Brabham-Alfa (4) Elf-Tyrrell (5) Wolf (6) Ligier-Matra (7) Copersucar (8) McLaren (9) Williams & Arrows (11) Shadow (12) Renault (13) Surtees & Ensign.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] A single non-championship Formula One race was held in 1978: the BRDC International Trophy, staged at Silverstone.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] This was the last time this event was run under Formula One regulations.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1978-formula-one-season] The race was won by future World Champion Keke Rosberg, driving in only his second Formula One event.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] on 76 points in his last season with the team.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The **1989 FIA Formula One World Championship** was the 43rd season of FIA Formula One motor racing.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] It began on 26 March and ended on 5 November.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Alain Prost won his third Drivers' Championship, and McLaren won its second consecutive Constructors' Championship; its fifth overall.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The Drivers' Championship was decided in controversial circumstances at the penultimate race of the season in Japan, when Prost and teammate Ayrton Senna, who needed to win the race, collided in the closing laps.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Prost retired while Senna rejoined the track after a push start and crossed the line first, only to be disqualified for not rejoining the track correctly.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This handed Prost the title, his last with McLaren before joining Ferrari in 1990.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The season also saw an unprecedented number of entries, with 21 constructors originally entered, fielding a total of 40 cars.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] However, FIRST Racing withdrew from the championship before the opening race, leaving 20 constructors fielding a total of 39 cars, which remains the highest entry in the modern era.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This year was the first year of the new mandatory 3.5 litre engine formula following the FIA's ban on turbocharged engines following the conclusion of the previous season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Renault also returned as engine supplier for the first time since 1986 with both Renault and Honda developing engines with a V10 configuration, an engine configuration never previously used in Formula One.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] As of 2025, this was the last time Honda and the same engine manufacturer won both the Formula One and MotoGP world manufacturers' titles in the same year.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The following teams and drivers competed in the 1989 FIA Formula One World Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] FIRST Racing injected material into their chassis in order to pass a mandatory FIA pre-season crash test, however, it made its car significantly overweight and they withdrew before the opening Brazilian Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] After this, they instead focused on the Formula 3000 series.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Changes to the technical regulations, including the outlawing of forced-induction engines, contributed to the bumper entry.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] McLaren, having won fifteen of the sixteen races in 1988, kept their successful driver line-up of 1985 and 1986 World Champion Alain Prost and defending champion Ayrton Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] They would drive the new MP4/5 powered by a Honda V10 engine.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Ferrari completed the signing of British driver Nigel Mansell, taking the place of Michele Alboreto alongside Austrian Gerhard Berger.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The new 640, designed by John Barnard, featured a semi-automatic electronic gearbox, the first of its kind, as well as the team's first 12-cylinder engine since 1980.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Williams recruited Belgian driver Thierry Boutsen from Benetton as Mansell's replacement, alongside veteran Italian Riccardo Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The team had also done a deal with Renault, returning to F1 after a three-year break, that would see them have exclusive use of the French company's V10 engines.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] For most of the season, Williams ran with the FW12C, an updated version of their 1988 car, before the new FW13 was introduced at the Portuguese Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Lotus kept their 1988 line-up of triple World Champion Nelson Piquet and Satoru Nakajima, but lost their Honda engines.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The new Lotus 101, designed by Frank Dernie, used the Judd V8 engine instead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Benetton retained Alessandro Nannini and signed British rookie Johnny Herbert to replace Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] However, Herbert was still recovering from severe foot injuries sustained in a Formula 3000 crash at Brands Hatch, and was eventually replaced by McLaren test driver Emanuele Pirro.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Benetton continued as the de facto works Ford team, but had to make do with the Cosworth DFR-powered 1988 car, the B188, until the new HB-powered B189 was introduced at the French Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Tyrrell retained Jonathan Palmer and took back Alboreto, who had previously driven for the team between 1981 and 1983.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] After a sponsorship dispute, Alboreto was replaced by French newcomer Jean Alesi, who at the same time was on his way to winning the F3000 championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The Brabham team returned after missing 1988, with Stefano Modena and Martin Brundle (fresh from winning the 1988 World Sports Prototype Championship) driving the Judd-powered BT58.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Both drivers were forced to pre-qualify for the first half of the season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The French Larrousse team continued running Lola chassis, but ditched the Ford Cosworth V8 engines in favour of the new Lamborghini V12, designed by Mauro Forghieri.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The team started the year with their 1988 line-up of Yannick Dalmas and Philippe Alliot, but Dalmas was recovering from Legionnaires' disease and was eventually replaced by Éric Bernard, who in turn made way for Alboreto.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Zakspeed, having produced their own turbo engines since their debut in 1985, were forced to switch to an outside supplier in the form of Yamaha, the Japanese company appearing in F1 for the first time with its own V8 engine.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Their new car, the 891, was designed by Gustav Brunner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] West German Bernd Schneider, in his second year with the team, and Japan's Aguri Suzuki were both forced to pre-qualify throughout the season .
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Osella were one of several teams to expand from one car to two, with Nicola Larini being joined by veteran Piercarlo Ghinzani, returning for a third stint with the team.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The all-new FA1M was powered by the Ford Cosworth DFR.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Ligier retained French veteran René Arnoux and signed newcomer Olivier Grouillard, who replaced experienced Swede Stefan Johansson.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The team also switched from Judd engines to the Ford Cosworth DFR, powering the new JS33.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] AGS had retained Philippe Streiff for 1989, but the Frenchman crashed heavily at Rio while testing prior to the Brazilian Grand Prix, suffering spinal injuries which left him as a quadriplegic and ended his racing career.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] His place was taken by Gabriele Tarquini, who had planned to drive for the Italian FIRST team that year before they pulled out.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] AGS also expanded to two cars, the second originally being driven by Joachim Winkelhock, younger brother of the late Manfred Winkelhock.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] After FIRST Racing withdrew from the championship, the only entirely new team for 1989 was Onyx Grand Prix, who had previously enjoyed success as the semi-works March team in Formula Two and Formula 3000.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The Onyx ORE-1, designed by Alan Jenkins and powered by the Ford Cosworth DFR, was driven by Johansson and Belgian rookie Bertrand Gachot, who would eventually be replaced by Finnish newcomer JJ Lehto.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] As was the tradition in Formula One in the 1980s, pre-season testing took place at the Jacarepaguá Autodrome in the city of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Teams would travel there for 10 days in March to test and acclimatise to Rio's very hot and humid weather.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The 1989 testing sessions saw several major accidents.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Thierry Boutsen crashed heavily in his Williams, and later, Frenchman Philippe Streiff crashed violently at the third corner, a fast, flat out left hander called *Suspiro*.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The AGS-Ford he was driving broke its rear suspension and he went head-on into the barriers.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The impact broke the car's roll-over bar, and Streiff suffered severe back injuries and was left in a coma.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He survived but was permanently paralyzed from the neck down.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Formula One arrived at Jacarepaguá as V10 and V12 engines were introduced.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The race in Brazil included a qualifying session where Riccardo Patrese started on the front row alongside Ayrton Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Thierry Boutsen qualified fourth, while Gerhard Berger and Alain Prost qualified in the following positions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The race started with a bang, as Senna's hopes at a home Grand Prix victory were dashed after a clash with Berger in the first turn.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] In what would prove to be a regular occurrence during the season, the semi-automatic transmission in the Ferrari 640 allowed Berger to get a lightning start from 3rd on the grid and he attempted to go inside of Senna and Patrese into the turn.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna was squeezed between Patrese and Berger, and lost the front wing of his car.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Patrese got through unscathed and in the lead of his record-breaking 177th Grand Prix start whilst Berger was out on the spot (the first of ten straight retirements for the Austrian driver) while Senna was forced to pit for repairs and would finish the race two laps down in eleventh place.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The final step of the podium was taken by local Maurício Gugelmin.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Grand Prix debutant Johnny Herbert, Derek Warwick and Alessandro Nannini scored the remaining points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He lost over 20 seconds in a slow pit stop and only finished 17.8 seconds behind Mansell at the finish suggesting a win (which would have been both his and Arrows' first) or podium place had gone begging.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] During the awards ceremony, Mansell cut his hand open on the trophy, ending the celebration early.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This was to be the last race at this fast, flat and abrasive Jacarepaguá circuit in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Formula One would move to a shortened Interlagos circuit in Senna's hometown of São Paulo for the 1990 season onwards.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] At Imola in Italy, "normal service" was resumed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] McLaren settled on the front row of the grid and stayed that way for the race, with Mansell's Ferrari retiring midway with gearbox issues.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This forced the race to be stopped after the fuel spilled all over Berger's car burst into flames after the car came to a standstill.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Berger miraculously survived with just a broken rib, shoulder bone and burns to his back and hands, due to rescue crews removing him from the wreck in less than 60 secs.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He gave a thumbs up and the race was restarted not too long after.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Patrese's engine failed and Boutsen was disqualified (but he got his 4th position back in an appeal), so the third place was taken by the Benetton Ford of Alessandro Nannini.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Warwick and Tyrrell's Jonathan Palmer secured the remaining point paying positions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] After the Grand Prix, Prost seemed disgruntled and said he wished to not make a comment on the race, other than that "orders were not respected".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Before the race at Monaco, Prost said he wanted "nothing to do with (Senna)" and refused to speak with him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] With Berger out, there were 29 cars in qualifying instead of 30, because Ferrari did not have a replacement driver.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna had scored his third pole of the season, with the number 2 car of Prost again alongside.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna went on to win by almost a whole minute over Prost while Stefano Modena secured a valuable third for the underfunded Brabham team on its return to Formula One after a year out.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This result effectively allowed Brabham to avoid prequalifying in the second half of the season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Modena, however, failed to score any points in any other Grand Prix in 1989.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Alex Caffi finished 4th in the Dallara while Michele Alboreto secured his first points since leaving Ferrari for Tyrrell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Martin Brundle scored the remaining point by finishing 6th.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] During practice Prost revealed his discontent with Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] According to Prost the pair had an agreement that if they were leading, whoever won the start would not be challenged by the other at the first corner, an agreement he previously had with former teammates Niki Lauda and Keke Rosberg.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Despite Marlboro's John Hogan supporting Prost's story by stating he was present when the agreement was made, Senna continued to deny that any such agreement existed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He also contended that the corner he passed Prost at, Tosa, was actually the third turn on the Imola circuit after Tamburello and Villeneuve.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] At the Autódromo Hermanos Rodríguez in Mexico City, Mexico, Gerhard Berger made a return despite continued pain in his fingers.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] However, transmission and gearbox problems forced the Ferraris to retire from point-scoring positions for the third race straight.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] While they lamented their results, McLaren and Senna took a third win on the trot by a differing choice of tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Prost's choice, and the wrong set of tyres being given to him at a pit stop (which prompted team boss Ron Dennis to issue Prost a public apology after the race), sent him down the order to fifth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Patrese was second for Williams, while Alboreto doubled his efforts in Monaco by scoring third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Alessandro Nannini finished 4th while Gabriele Tarquini was able to bring his barely pre-qualified AGS home in sixth for a well-celebrated point.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna won the start and built up a small lead over Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna suffered an electrical problem when leading the race and his engine started to misfire.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He signalled Prost through to a lead he would not lose on lap 34.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Williams ended up being the only team to finish with both cars as the dirty track and unforgiving concrete walls ended six races, with the heat and dust cutting out many more.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] One driver, Alessandro Nannini, suffered from a severely sore neck after a crash in the morning warm-up and retired from fourth place on lap 10.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Mansell and Berger suffered with the Ferrari V12s cutting out from identical alternator failures and both eventually retired.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Patrese's second gave him third place in the championship, while Prost took the lead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Ecstatic Phoenix native Eddie Cheever celebrated his and his team's first podium of the season at his own home Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The Brabhams, on the other hand, continued their lacklustre return, both drivers retiring with worn-out brakes.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Dallara's Alex Caffi was the victim of a bizarre crash.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Holding down 5th place, he was put into the wall on lap 52 by his own teammate Andrea de Cesaris when he was trying to lap him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The notorious de Cesaris later claimed he did not even know Caffi was there trying to lap him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The race of attrition saw Christian Danner score a surprise 4th place in his Rial, while Herbert and Boutsen rounded out the scoring zone.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The race ran for the full 2 hours and was flagged after 75 of the scheduled 81 laps.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Alain Prost scored his only ever win in the US, while Cheever's 3rd place was his final podium in Formula One.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Before the race with the heat and practice times proving some 10–15 seconds per lap slower than predicted, a petition was circulated among the teams requesting the race be reduced to 70 laps.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] All team managers signed the petition with the exception of Ken Tyrrell which meant the race was not officially shortened.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Ironically, this would work against his team when Jonathan Palmer lost a certain 4th place after his Tyrrell-Ford ran out of fuel on lap 69.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Had the race been flagged after 70 laps, Palmer would have finished 4th having already been lapped by Prost instead of running out of fuel and being classified as 9th and last.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The Canadian Grand Prix in Montreal was run in wet conditions and provided many retirements, but also a new winner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna was comfortably leading with only three laps to go when engine problems forced him to retire, handing Boutsen his first victory.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Patrese came home second to make it a 1–2 finish for Williams, the first time a team other than McLaren had achieved this since Ferrari in Monza the previous year.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Making up for his Phoenix indiscretion, Andrea de Cesaris picked up third for Dallara, the first ever podium finish for the small Italian team.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Triple World Champion Nelson Piquet picked up his and Lotus's first points of the year by finishing 4th, only 4.8 seconds behind de Cesaris.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] René Arnoux would score the final points of his career by finishing 5th for Ligier.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Caffi snatched the final point by finishing 6th.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] In his home race at the Paul Ricard circuit near Marseille, Prost took pole and won convincingly, while fellow Frenchman Jean Alesi made his debut for the Tyrrell team, replacing Alboreto due to the team now having Camel sponsorship which conflicted with his personal Marlboro sponsorship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This proved to pay off as Alesi secured a fourth-place finish (having run second at one stage).
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Nigel Mansell ended Ferrari's run of retirements with a secure second while Patrese was third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Swede Stefan Johansson finished 5th, scoring the Onyx team's first points, and Olivier Grouillard took the final points paying position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna, meanwhile, was forced to retire straight after the restart with a differential problem.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The race had to be restarted when, on the first lap, Gugelmin caused a major first corner accident when he lost control of his March, flew into the air and landed on Mansell's rear wing.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Luckily, no one was hurt and all drivers managed to take the restart.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The French marshals were widely criticised for tipping the upside down March back on its wheels before Gugelmin had a chance to get out of the car.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The British Grand Prix at the very fast Silverstone circuit proved much the same – McLaren front row, Senna retiring from the lead after a spin, and Prost winning.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Mansell finished second in his home race to please the British fans, whose Mansellmania coupled with the tifosi made for hysteria.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Nannini finished third, Piquet 4th, while both Minardis, Martini followed by Pérez-Sala, took the final 2 points positions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] At this, the halfway point of the championship, Prost's lead over Senna had increased to 20 points; Britain was the 4th consecutive race Senna had retired from- and Prost had won 3 of those 4 races.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Despite much talk, he downplayed the thought of a third championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] "I don't want to start talking about the championship, getting into all that," he said, "but I'm much happier now, yes.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] At Hockenheim in Germany (another very fast circuit) however, Senna's bad luck ended after scoring a treble – pole, fastest lap and the win, but he had to fight almost all the way with Prost to do so.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] After both McLarens suffered bad mid-race stops for tyres, Prost emerged in the lead and looked to have the race in his grasp but lost top gear with less than two laps to go.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Berger's pointless season continued with a tire puncture causing a spectacular accident and robbing him of a possible podium.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Mansell picked up a third place and mused everyone's thoughts: "If any of the circuits in the world is ideal for McLaren-Honda, it's Hockenheim." Patrese, Piquet and Warwick took the remaining three points-paying positions, respectively.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The dirty Hungaroring near Budapest provided an almost gripless practice and qualifying, that eventually led to the first non-McLaren pole position of the year – Riccardo Patrese made a Senna-like performance with a 0.31 gap between him and Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Another surprise was the equally impressive Alex Caffi, who scored third with a time less than a second slower than that of Patrese – in a car that had been notoriously midfield.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Mansell was over two seconds off Patrese's time of an impressive 1:19.7, whilst Berger constantly complained of gear shift troubles – even asking the team to change the gearbox pre-race, which they did not.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This eventually cost him a point scoring position, as the gearbox went on to fail.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Countering this was Mansell's impressive 12th-to-first race, even overtaking Senna in the area he excelled most, lapping back markers – an impressive move on a track notorious for mediocre and unpassable races.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He went on to compare the race to his win at Silverstone two years earlier and dedicated it to the late Enzo Ferrari, a year after the Old Man's death.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Caffi's race was the exact counterpoint of Mansell's – despite a strong start he finished a lonely seventh, earning no points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna finished nearly half a minute behind Mansell in second, while Prost again suffered problems and finished fourth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Patrese retired from the lead and Boutsen finished third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The final two points positions were taken by American Eddie Cheever in the Arrows, finishing 5th, followed by Piquet in 6th.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] A wet Spa showcased Senna's wet weather skills at their best.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] 'Magic' (Senna's nickname during the wet) shone that day to give him another win despite engine troubles that also befell Prost with Mansell in third saying that problems like that he could certainly use – he finished less than two seconds behind Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Boutsen, Nannini and Warwick, in that order, took the final three points-paying positions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The Italian Grand Prix at the Monza Autodrome near Milan sealed the end of two things: Gerhard Berger's terrible season (he scored a second place on both the grid and in the race) and Prost's relationship with McLaren.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Having become progressively distanced from the team due to his conflict with Senna, he announced his switch to Ferrari for 1990, and after inheriting the race win when Senna retired from the lead late on, he proceeded to give the trophy he had won to the tifosi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] McLaren boss Ron Dennis' usual composure was shattered and he hurled his trophy at his driver's feet, storming off (Dennis was unhappy with Prost giving the trophy to the tifosi as contractually all trophies won were the property of the team).
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Prost later said it was an unsatisfactory win and that he did not hold out much hope for the championship despite his points lead as he felt Honda were clearly favouring Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The final points went to Patrese, who finished fourth, followed by Brit Martin Brundle for Brabham and Jean Alesi in the Tyrrell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Mansell was subsequently banned from the next race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] This was Prost's twelfth points finish of the season, which meant that he now had to drop points as only the eleven best points finishes counted, but he still led by 24 points with three races left.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Johansson finished a fine third for the struggling Onyx team (a result that meant they did not have to go through pre-qualifying in the first half of 1990), marveling at the car's performance on a low-grip track and speaking of optimism for Spain.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Nannini finished in fourth, while Pierluigi Martini qualified fifth and finished in that position, also leading for one lap; the only time in the Minardi team's 21-year history that it led a Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Tyrrell racing finished in sixth for the 2nd consecutive race, although it was Jonathan Palmer that earned the point for them in Portugal.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The new Williamses, however, suffered near-simultaneous and identical motor blow-outs.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna kept the championship alive in Spain by taking pole position and leading throughout, beating Berger by almost half a minute at the Jerez circuit near Seville.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Prost drove a cautious race and finished third, dropping more points, but it meant that Senna had to win both remaining races to have any chance of beating the Frenchman to the title.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Meanwhile, Alesi scored another strong fourth place for the Tyrrell team.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Finishing 5th was Patrese ahead of Philippe Alliot who would score the only point of the season for the Larrousse-Lola team.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Then the Formula One circus arrived at Suzuka, Japan near Nagoya for the now infamous penultimate round for the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Prost said he would not leave the door open for his teammate, who he felt had made far too many risky moves on him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna took pole, but Prost beat him away from the grid and led by 1.4 seconds by the end of the first lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] By lap 15, however, Senna was all over the back of Prost's McLaren after moving through both Williams and Benettons.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He whittled down Prost's 5 second lead to just under a second by lap 30, but the latter pulled a few seconds ahead by the 35th lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] By the end of lap 46, with 7 to go, the gap was just over a second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna, further back than he had been earlier in the race, made a move on Prost in the chicane before the start-finish straight.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Prost turned in early, hitting Senna, and the two skidded into the escape road and both engines stalled.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna, however, got a push from the marshals to restart his dead engine and returned to the track.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] After pitting for repairs, Senna worked his way past both Williams and the Benettons to take a three-second victory.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] However, his altercation with Prost seven laps earlier meant he had missed the chicane and, according to FIA and FISA president Jean Marie Balestre, had not completed the lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] It is worth noting that many drivers in previous races had used the escape roads near chicanes after on-track incidents, as is customary, without receiving penalties.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] A penalty could have been given for restarting his stalled engine, which is technically illegal, but the stewards only considered the shortcut for the penalty.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] He was disqualified and Nannini revelled in his first Grand Prix victory.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The new Williams FW13s of Patrese and Boutsen finished second and third, putting them five points ahead of the Ferrari team in the race for second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Piquet, Brundle and Warwick clinched the remaining point-paying positions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] With the matter hanging in the air, Senna went on record saying it was a plot and conspiracy against him by Balestre, who he said favoured Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna would comment again on the matter after sealing his 1991 championship, reiterating his belief that he had been unfairly treated.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The final round at Adelaide saw the race run under heavy rain.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Prost elected to withdraw at the end of the first lap in such torrentially wet conditions and would score no points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Senna, who considered quitting in protest of his disqualification in the previous race, was convinced to race by friends and team members (Ron Dennis told him: "if you stop, they've won").
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Starting from pole, by lap ten he had over 30 seconds to the Williams pair and counting.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] Instead of relaxing, he continued to push in poor visibility.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] On lap 13, he ran into the rear of Brundle's Brabham and was out of the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The two Williams Renaults scored a double podium finish with Boutsen winning and Patrese coming in third, Nannini finishing between them, despite Williams being a strong proponent of not starting in such conditions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The remaining points were scored by Satoru Nakajima in his single scoring-zone finish of the season, Emanuele Pirro (Benetton's mid-season replacement for the dismissed Herbert) in the first time since Round 1 that Benetton's points came from another driver as well as Nannini, and Martini.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p01] The Australian Grand Prix was overshadowed by the ongoing controversy surrounding the Japanese race, but once the appeals had been considered, Prost was crowned the champion for the third time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p02] For the Drivers' Championship, the best eleven results were counted, while, for the Constructors' Championship, all rounds were counted.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p02] † Driver did not finish the Grand Prix, but was classified as he completed over 90% of the race distance.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-formula-one-world-championship-p02] The 1989 season also included a single event which did not count towards the World Championship, the Formula One Indoor Trophy at the Bologna Motor Show.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The **1989 Japanese Grand Prix** (formally the **XV Fuji Television Japanese Grand Prix**) was a Formula One motor race held on 22 October 1989 at Suzuka Circuit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] It was the 15th and penultimate round of the 1989 Formula One season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The 53-lap race was won by Alessandro Nannini for the Benetton team, from a sixth position start.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Riccardo Patrese finished second for the Williams team, with Thierry Boutsen third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The race is one of the most famous in F1 history, as the culmination of Alain Prost and Ayrton Senna's tumultuous two-year rivalry as teammates at McLaren.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] With Prost leading the championship by 16 points, Senna had to win both races to possibly defend the championship, and with Prost leading the race, too, on lap 47 of 53 the Brazilian tried to pass at the inside of the chicane.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Senna failed to get ahead, failed to turn in, and made both cars go straight, with his front wheels always behind Prost's wheels.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Both cars came to a stop next to each other at the entry of the escape road, both had missed the entry to the chicane.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Prost abandoned his stalled car, while Senna got his restarted by marshals, weaved through the barriers, rejoined the track after the chicane, made a pit stop to change his front wing, and overhauled Alessandro Nannini to take the checkered flag.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Following the race Senna was disqualified for getting an advantage by missing the chicane, handing the win to Nannini and the title to Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] As in 1988, the McLaren team had been dominant throughout 1989.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Going into this race, Prost had a 16-point lead in the Drivers' Championship over Senna, 76 to 60.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The Brazilian had won six races to the Frenchman's four, including the previous race in Spain, but had only finished in the points on one other occasion, while Prost had only finished out of the points once all season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Therefore, Senna had to win both this race and the final race in Australia to have any chance of retaining his World Drivers' Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] However, if Senna did win the last two races, he would be champion regardless of where Prost finished, due to the dropped scores system.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Prost had told team boss Ron Dennis before the race that in the past he had left the door open if Senna challenged so as not to take both team cars out, but he would not be leaving the door open on this day.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Nicola Larini was fastest in the Friday morning pre-qualifying session for the second Grand Prix in a row, the Osella driver just edging out Philippe Alliot in his Larrousse-Lola.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] A surprising third place was the Zakspeed of Bernd Schneider, who had not pre-qualified since the first race of the season in Brazil.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The car's underpowered Yamaha engine had undergone some testing and development work since the last race, with some clear improvement made.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] "Our season starts here," Schneider said.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The fourth pre-qualifying spot went to Michele Alboreto in the other Lola.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Larini's team-mate Piercarlo Ghinzani missed out this time in fifth place, with Roberto Moreno sixth in his Coloni.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The Onyx team failed to get either car through to the main qualifying sessions for the first time since the third round at Monaco, as Stefan Johansson could only manage seventh after a fuel pump failure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Zakspeed's improvement could only help Aguri Suzuki to eighth place, his fifteenth straight failure to pre-qualify.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Oscar Larrauri was ninth in the EuroBrun, ahead of the other Onyx of JJ Lehto.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The AGS team had spent three days testing in France, but were both well off the pace in this session, with only Enrico Bertaggia's Coloni below them on the time sheets, as the Italian failed to post a time.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] As expected, the two McLarens dominated qualifying.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Even so, Senna was easily the class of the field, posting a time over a second and a half faster than teammate Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The Ferraris of Gerhard Berger and Nigel Mansell filled the second row, with Berger just edging his own teammate into fourth place by two-tenths of a second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The Williams of Riccardo Patrese was half a second behind Mansell in fifth place, and joining him on row three was fellow Italian Alessandro Nannini in his Benetton-Ford using the development HBA4 V8 engine.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Behind Nannini positions were closely contested, with only six-tenths of a second covering the next six qualifying times, including that of former World Champion Nelson Piquet's Lotus-Judd in eleventh position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Jonathan Palmer's Tyrrell-Ford took the final grid slot in twenty-sixth place, while four failed to qualify (including former Ferrari drivers René Arnoux and Michele Alboreto who between them had won 12 Grands Prix), with nine drivers failing to pre-qualify.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Bernd Schneider qualified the Zakspeed-Yamaha for only its second race of the season (he also qualified for the season opener in Brazil).
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Schneider qualified 21st, only 4.851 seconds slower than Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Schneider's teammate Aguri Suzuki was not as successful in his home Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] After making his F1 debut for the Larrousse team at Suzuka in 1988, Suzuki recorded his 15th straight failure to pre-qualify the under-powered Zakspeed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] To improve his straight-line speed, Prost had his Gurney flap removed before the race, without Senna's knowledge, as revealed by Formula One journalist Maurice Hamilton.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] At the start, Prost got away much faster than Senna as he was hoping, instantly wiping out the Brazilian's pole position advantage.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] In fact, Senna's start was so poor that Gerhard Berger managed to get alongside him from his third place on the grid.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] But Senna's McLaren had the inside line into the first corner, and he managed to keep the Ferrari behind him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] With a race-setup now clearly superior to his teammate's, over the first half of the race Prost steadily built his lead up to almost six seconds, and then Senna lost an additional two seconds due to a slow pitstop.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] However, with a new set of tyres on the balance of power shifted, and the reigning World Champion began to reel in the French double World Champion.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Behind the leading pair, after his initial charge, Gerhard Berger's Ferrari gearbox failed on lap 34, and the sister Ferrari of Nigel Mansell suffered engine failure nine laps later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] With the Scuderia's cars gone, all real challenge to the McLaren charge had evaporated.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The only opposition left for Senna and Prost was each other as they were drawing away from the new third placed man Alessandro Nannini.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The Italian's Benetton used the less powerful, but more reliable, HBA1 engine in the race and not the development HBA4.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] His teammate Emanuele Pirro did use the development V8 in the race, and while he was not as quick as Nannini, he did use it to move up to 10th after starting 22nd.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Pirro's race ended on lap 33 after a collision at the hairpin with Andrea de Cesaris where Pirro ran into the back of his fellow Italian's Dallara.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Senna finally caught Prost on lap 40, and for the next five laps the gap between the two remained at approximately one second as the two McLaren drivers tried to position themselves tactically.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Prost had greater top speed on the straights, while Senna's high-downforce settings gave him the advantage through the corners.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] On lap 47 Senna used his greater cornering speed to make sure that he remained close behind Prost's car through the challenging, double-apex Spoon Corner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] This put Senna's car directly in the aerodynamic tow from the leading McLaren, negating much of Prost's straight line advantage.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Through the infamous 130R, ultra high-speed, left curve, Senna cut Prost's lead still further, putting his MP4/5 only two car lengths behind his rival.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The next corner after 130R is the chicane, the second-slowest corner on the circuit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] As Prost began to brake for the corner Senna dove to the inside but never came fully alongside, his front wheels remaining just behind those of Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Prost then turned towards the apex to take the normal racing line, but with Senna there on the inside line, the two cars made contact.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] With their wheels locked and their engines stalled, the two cars came to a halt at the mouth of the partially blocked chicane escape road, thus having missed the chicane entry.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] As the vehicles were directly in the line of any possible out of control cars, the marshals hurried to clear them.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] While Prost unbuckled his belts and left his car in neutral to be removed, Senna gestured to the marshals to push him down the escape road.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] As the McLaren was pushed forward, Senna used the forward motion to restart his engine, and after it fired he immediately accelerated down the escape road, weaving between the temporary chicane bollards arranged in the roadway.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Although his car was running, Senna's MP4/5 had suffered damage to its front wing during the collision, and while Prost slowly wandered back to the nearby pit lane, Senna had to complete almost an entire lap of the circuit before pitting for a repair.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Once his nosecone had been replaced Senna continued the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Senna did not take long to catch Nannini's Benetton-Ford.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] He passed the Italian only two laps after having his nosecone replaced, in exactly the same place as the collision with Prost had occurred.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Unlike Prost, Nannini had a different car, different engine, thus didn't put up a significant fight, a locked wheel the only indication of how hard he tried to keep Senna behind.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Two laps later Senna took the chequered flag.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Nannini finished in second place, followed by the two Williams-Renaults of Riccardo Patrese and Thierry Boutsen who had driven in tandem and off the pace throughout the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] The only other driver on the same lap as the podium was Nelson Piquet in 4th; almost a lap down, but still far better placed than the eleventh position he started his Lotus-Judd in, mostly due to the race's high attrition rate.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Only eleven of the twenty-six starters were still running at the finish.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Behind Piquet were two British drivers who also benefited from the misfortune of others, and while Martin Brundle's sixth-place finish was remarkable enough, Derek Warwick had come from 25th at the back row of the grid in his Arrows to take a seventh place.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] In a ploy that worked a treat for him, before the race Warwick had taken the extraordinary step of removing virtually all downforce from his car in the hopes that the extra straight line speed would give him an advantage.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Immediately after the race, Senna was disqualified by race stewards for missing the chicane following his collision with Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Nannini was awarded the victory as a result, and he took the podium ceremony with Patrese and Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] This would prove to be Nannini's only victory in a Formula One career that was cut short by a helicopter crash almost exactly a year later, which severed his right forearm.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Senna's disqualification also meant that it was mathematically impossible for him to overhaul Prost's points total, and so the 1989 Drivers' Championship went to the Frenchman.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] As he had gained no competitive advantage by missing the chicane, Senna and McLaren attempted to appeal the disqualification ruling.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] At the FISA hearing in Paris later the same week, Senna's disqualification was not only upheld, but an additional US$100,000 fine and suspended six-month ban were imposed on the driver (FISA also labeled Senna as a "dangerous driver").
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1989-japanese-grand-prix] Ever since the incident, there has been much debate as to whether Prost intentionally ran into Senna, whether Senna was overambitious in his overtaking move, or whether the collision was simply a racing incident between two embittered teammates.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] won the 1990 Formula One World Championship for Constructors.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] placed second in the 1990 Formula One World Championship for Constructors.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] placed third in the 1990 Formula One World Championship for Constructors.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The **1990 FIA Formula One World Championship** was the 44th season of FIA Formula One motor racing.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] It featured the 1990 Formula One World Championship for Drivers and the 1990 Formula One World Championship for Constructors, which were contested concurrently over a sixteen-race series that commenced on 11 March and ended on 4 November.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Ayrton Senna won the Drivers' Championship for the second time, and McLaren-Honda won their third consecutive Constructors' Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The championship featured a dramatic battle between Senna and former teammate Alain Prost, who had made the switch to Ferrari.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost mounted Ferrari's first title challenge for several years, and led the championship after three consecutive mid-season wins.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna fought back strongly and went into the penultimate round at the Suzuka circuit in Japan with a nine-point lead over Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] There, Senna took pole position only for Prost to beat him off the line; the Brazilian driver then drove into the Frenchman at the first corner, putting both out and thus settling the championship in Senna's favour.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] This was the second year in succession that the two drivers had collided at Suzuka.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna admitted the following year that the collision was deliberate, as he was furious that Prost had been able to start on the clean side of the grid and had decided that he was not going to allow the Frenchman to 'make the corner' should he lose the start.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The following teams and drivers competed in the 1990 FIA Formula One World Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Another eight driver switches had happened over the winter, within the lower-ranking teams.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The United States Grand Prix was moved from June to March to become the first round.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The Brazilian Grand Prix was returned to the Interlagos Circuit for the first time since 1980, with a shorter track layout after a major renovation of the facility.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The Canadian Grand Prix was moved to be before the Mexican Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Unexpected rain in qualifying led to a grid with Gerhard Berger on pole position with Pierluigi Martini second in the Minardi, Andrea de Cesaris third in the Dallara, Jean Alesi fourth in the Tyrrell, Ayrton Senna down in fifth and Nelson Piquet sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Alesi took the lead at the start ahead of Berger, de Cesaris, Senna, Martini and Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Alesi pulled away and Berger was dropping back Senna passed de Cesaris.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger hit a wall on lap 9 forcing him to pit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He charged back but later retired with clutch problems.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Alesi was 8.2 seconds ahead but Senna started to reel him in.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna attacked on lap 34 but Alesi defended and kept the lead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna overtook Alesi one lap later and pulled away to win.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Both Ferraris retired with Alain Prost retiring on lap 21 with an oil leak and Nigel Mansell on lap 49 with clutch problems.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] After that, Thierry Boutsen passed Piquet to take third with Stefano Modena's Brabham and Satoru Nakajima's Tyrrell getting the final points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The Brazilian Grand Prix had returned to the Interlagos Autodrome in São Paulo for the first time since 1980, having been at the Jacarepagua Riocentro Autodrome in Rio de Janeiro for 9 previous seasons consecutively, and 1978.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The circuit had been shortened from 4.9 mi (7.9 km) to 2.6 mi (4.2 km).
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] During qualifying, Senna and Berger were 1–2 with Boutsen and Patrese 3–4 and the Ferraris of Nigel Mansell and Alain Prost behind them.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Senna led Berger, Boutsen, Prost, Patrese and Mansell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Boutsen passed Berger early on but could not keep up with Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the stops, Boutsen ran into a tyre and had to change his nose cone, dropping back to 11th and some good work from the Ferrari crew got Prost ahead of Berger and Mansell ahead of Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna was ahead of Prost, Berger, Mansell, Patrese and Alesi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna, 10 seconds ahead of everybody hit the backmarker, former teammate Nakajima, forcing him to pit and drop back to third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] With just a few laps to go, Patrese retired with a broken oil cooler.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost won from Berger, Senna, Mansell, the recovering Boutsen and Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] There was a six-week gap before the San Marino round, at the Autodromo Enzo e Dino Ferrari near Bologna in Italy; a number of changes were made to most of the cars during this period.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] An almost identical grid to Brazil saw Senna, Berger, Patrese, Boutsen, Mansell and Prost line up after qualifying.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Senna and Berger got away well but Boutsen sliced ahead of Patrese to take third with Mansell and Prost behind.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On the next lap, a stone sliced through Senna's wheelrim, spinning him into a sand trap and out of the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Boutsen pulled away from Berger but his engine blew on lap 18.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Soon Mansell passed Patrese and then attacked Berger.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger closed the door and Mansell spun without hitting anything nor losing a place.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He set off after Berger again but retired with engine problems.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the second stops, Nannini got ahead of Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Patrese closed in on Berger and passed him on lap 51.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Patrese pulled away and won his first Grand Prix since South Africa in 1983 from Berger, Nannini, Prost, Piquet and Alesi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] In Monaco, Senna took pole but Prost was second with Alesi third ahead of Patrese, Berger and Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Berger collided with Prost at Mirabeau, blocking the track and stopping the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The second start was all right and Senna led from Prost, Alesi, Berger, Patrese and Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The race settled down and nothing changed until lap 30 when Prost retired with a battery failure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Then Mansell hit the back of Boutsen and was forced to pit and changed his front wing.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Behind, Mansell was charging through the field and passed Boutsen to take fourth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] But then he was sidelined with the same problem as Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the front, Senna won from Alesi, Berger, Boutsen, Alex Caffi in the Arrows and Éric Bernard's Larrousse.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Canada was next and at the Circuit Gilles Villeneuve in Montreal the McLarens were 1–2 in qualifying with Senna ahead of Berger with Prost third, Nannini fourth, Piquet fifth and Boutsen sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The track was damp on race day and Berger jumped the start and then hesitated.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He got a 1-minute time penalty as well as allowing Senna to lead on the road.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna led Nannini, Alesi, Prost, Boutsen and Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The track began to dry and everyone pitted.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] But when Nannini rejoined, he hit a groundhog and had to pit again for repairs.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger took the lead on the road but he needed a minute to stay ahead at the end.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He charged and was a second quicker than the others as Boutsen spun off while battling Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna now led from Prost, Piquet, Mansell, Patrese and Derek Warwick.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Piquet after many laps finally passed Prost who was then attacked by Mansell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Patrese retired putting Berger to fifth (he got ahead of Warwick before).
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell passed Prost and slowly pulled away.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] With two laps to go, Berger got past Prost on aggregate but could not get ahead of Mansell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna won from Piquet, Mansell, Berger, Prost and Warwick.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] After Canada came the Autodromo Hermanos Rodriguez in Mexico City and Berger qualified on pole position with Patrese beside him and Senna third, Mansell fourth, Boutsen fifth and Alesi sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Patrese and Berger jumped Senna while Piquet got ahead of Boutsen and Mansell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Early on, Senna passed Patrese and Berger followed him through.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Patrese was dropping back and Piquet got by him as well.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Boutsen was the next to go through but at the same time Berger had a problem with his tyre and was forced to stop and dropped to 12th position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna lead from Piquet, Boutsen, Patrese, Mansell and Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Soon, Mansell passed Patrese and got Boutsen four laps later as Prost did the same to Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost sneaked ahead of Boutsen as Mansell closed in on Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell got ahead on lap 36 and Prost followed him through six laps later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Piquet soon stopped and dropped behind Nannini, Boutsen (who already stopped) and Berger.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger passed Boutsen on lap 47 and Nannini four laps later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost passed Mansell on lap 55 and they began to close in on Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost, passed Senna followed by Mansell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Then Mansell spun but at the same time Senna got a puncture that led to him retiring in the pits 4 laps before the end and allowing Berger to get third and close in to Mansell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] With a daring move Berger passed Mansell but Mansell charged back and attacked taking back second place after making an even more daring pass around the outside of Berger at the fastest corner on the track, the 180-degree Peraltada corner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost won with Mansell second making it a Ferrari 1–2 ahead of Berger, Nannini, Boutsen and Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] France was next, being held at the Paul Ricard circuit near the coastal city of Marseille.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The fans were wearing red and a Ferrari did take pole position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] However, it was not their hero Prost but Mansell who was ahead of Berger, Senna, Prost, Nannini and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Berger got past Mansell while Prost lost out as well.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger led with Mansell, Senna, Nannini, Patrese and Prost behind.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 2, Senna passed Mansell for second and soon after Prost passed Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The order stayed like that until Senna passed Berger who had been too hard on his tyres in the early stages.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Nannini and Piquet pitted early while Berger and Senna went too late.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell's and Prost's tyres lasted longer and thus they pitted late.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Riccardo Patrese went too late and was the big loser.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] This left the two Leyton Houses (they planned the race without a stop) ahead with a totally shuffled order behind them.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Ivan Capelli led Maurício Gugelmin, Prost, Nannini, Mansell and Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost then caught and passed Gugelmin who then went out with engine trouble.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] As Prost closed in on Capelli, Mansell in 8th place could not get by Berger, Piquet and Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Capelli continued to defend from Prost as Mansell went out with engine trouble.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Nannini moved into third but was then forced to retire with electrical trouble, while Prost finally passed Capelli with three laps to go.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost won ahead of Capelli, Senna, Piquet, Berger and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Britain was next and Mansell, roared on by his home fans at the fast Silverstone airfield circuit, took pole from Senna, followed by Berger, Boutsen, Prost and Alesi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna passed Mansell at the first corner and led for the first 11 laps before Mansell retook the lead; the Brazilian then spun on lap 14, dropping down to fifth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] As Prost passed Boutsen for third, Mansell began to have troubles with his gearbox.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger passed him for the lead on lap 22 but then began to suffer handling issues, enabling Mansell to re-pass him on lap 28.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Meanwhile, Prost closed up to both drivers, before passing Berger on lap 31 and then Mansell on lap 44 as the Englishman's gearbox issues worsened.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell remained second until lap 56 when his gearbox failed altogether; he promptly threw his gloves into the crowd and announced his retirement from Formula One at the end of the season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Capelli briefly ran third ahead of Berger before his fuel pipe broke; Berger's race then ended four laps from home with a throttle failure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] This left Prost to win by nearly 40 seconds from Boutsen, the Belgian driver in turn finishing four seconds ahead of Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Bernard, Piquet and Aguri Suzuki rounded out the top six.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the halfway stage of the season, Prost led the Drivers' Championship by two points from Senna, 41 to 39, with Berger third with 25 points, Piquet fourth with 18 and Boutsen fifth with 17.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] McLaren led the Constructors' Championship with 64 points, followed by Ferrari on 54, Williams on 27 and Benetton on 25.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start of the second half of the season, there was one change in pre-qualifying: Larrousse-Lola's five points meant that they were automatically promoted into main qualifying, dropping fellow French team Ligier into the Friday morning session.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Meanwhile, Coloni had terminated their unsuccessful partnership with Subaru and were now using Cosworth engines, although these failed to improve the team's performance.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the very fast, forested Hockenheimring, McLarens were 1–2 in qualifying, Senna ahead of Berger.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Ferraris were 3–4 with Prost ahead of Mansell and Williamses were 5–6 to complete the "Noah's Ark" (two-by-two) formation, Patrese ahead of Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Berger took off better than Senna but Senna just stayed ahead with Berger second, Prost third, Mansell fourth, Patrese fifth and Piquet sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] There were no changes until lap 11 when Piquet tried to pass Patrese and went through an escape road, allowing Nannini to get ahead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Three laps later Mansell went through the grass at Ostkurve without losing a place but damaging his car.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] It proved crucial as he retired two laps later, the damage being too great.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Meanwhile, Nannini passed Patrese as the top three stopped for tyres, the Williamses and Benettons planning to go without a stop.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Thus, Nannini led Senna, Patrese, Piquet, Berger and Prost.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Patrese's tyres were very badly damaged and he was forced to pit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost then passed Boutsen for fourth with Patrese following him two laps later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 34, Senna passed Nannini for the lead and pulled away.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna won from Nannini, Berger, Prost, Patrese and Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Hungary was next and at the Hungaroring in Mogyoród, the Williamses qualified ahead of the McLarens, Boutsen taking pole ahead of Patrese, Berger, Senna, Mansell and Alesi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Boutsen kept the lead but it was Berger who got away best and passed Patrese while Senna was worse and lost out to both Mansell and Alesi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Thus, it was Boutsen, Berger, Patrese, Mansell, Alesi and Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] It stayed like that until lap 21 when Senna passed Alesi for fifth but he was forced to pit on the next lap with a slow puncture.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Nannini soon passed Alesi to take fifth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The leaders stopped and Berger was the big loser with Nannini and Senna the big gainers, rising directly behind the Williams men.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The order was: Boutsen, Patrese, Nannini, Senna, Mansell and Berger.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Boutsen then pulled away while Patrese held up the others until Nannini streamed by with Senna following him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Patrese then pitted and dropped behind Piquet as Berger passed Mansell only for Mansell to get back at him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna tried to pass Nannini on lap 64 and tipped Nannini into a spin and retirement.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger tried to do the same thing on Mansell on lap 72 at the same corner with the same result – a collision but with both cars out.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Boutsen won ahead of Senna, Piquet, Patrese, Warwick and Bernard.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The financially troubled Monteverdi Onyx team pulled out of F1 before the Belgian round, which allowed the Ligier team to escape from pre-qualifying.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the historic Spa-Francorchamps circuit, McLaren were 1–2 with Senna on pole ahead of Berger, Prost, Boutsen, Mansell and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Piquet pushed Mansell off the road and soon Nakajima and Modena collided as well, causing the race to be stopped.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the second start, Senna took the lead while Boutsen sliced into second and Prost dropped to fifth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] However, Paolo Barilla crashed his Minardi heavily at Eau Rouge, sending debris all over the track and causing the race to be stopped again.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The third start was clean and Senna took the lead ahead of Berger, Prost, Boutsen, Patrese and Nannini.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 11, Mansell went into the pits with handling problems; he went back out but retired eight laps later.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 14, Prost sliced ahead of Berger who then pitted for tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna and Prost, separated by 2 seconds stopped at the same time but then Nannini who was planning to go without stopping came in between them.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Then both Patrese and Boutsen went out with gearbox troubles.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost passed Nannini and Berger tried the same but this time Nannini came back at him to keep the place.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 41, Nannini went wide and Berger sailed through to take third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna duly won from Prost, Berger, Nannini, Piquet and Gugelmin.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] With five races remaining, the Drivers' Championship now lay firmly between Senna with 63 points and Prost with 50.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger was third with 33, Boutsen fourth with 27, and Piquet fifth with 24.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] McLaren held a comfortable lead in the Constructors' Championship with 96 points against Ferrari's 63, with Williams third with 42, and Benetton fourth with 40.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] After Belgium came Italy and at the historic Monza Autodrome near Milan, Senna took pole again with Prost second, Berger third, Mansell fourth, Alesi fifth and Boutsen sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Berger raced past Prost while Alesi was jumped by both the Ferraris.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] But Warwick crashed at the Parabolica, bringing out the red flags.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] In the restart, Berger got past Prost and Alesi repeated his previous effort and had passed both Ferraris before the second chicane, so we had Senna leading Berger, Alesi, Prost, Mansell and Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Nothing changed until lap 18 when Boutsen retired with a suspension failure and Berger's tyres began to fade.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost then passed Berger and the stops did not change anything.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The top three then began to battle for the lead but none were able to close in on the other while Mansell continued to drop back, fighting a faulty throttle return spring.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna won from Prost, Berger, Mansell, Patrese and Nakajima.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] In Portugal, at the Estoril circuit near Lisbon, the Ferraris took 1–2 in qualifying with Mansell ahead of Prost, Senna, Berger, Patrese and Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Mansell got too much wheel spin and he slid across the track and almost took Prost out; as a result, the McLarens blasted by them with Piquet getting by Prost as well.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The order was: Senna, Berger, Mansell, Piquet, Prost and Boutsen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 13, Prost overtook Piquet for fourth and later Mansell went to the grass, allowing Prost to take third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell and Berger pitted soon as Prost passed Senna at the same time to lead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] These two soon pitted as well with a shuffled order: Senna, Mansell, Berger, Prost, Nannini and Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] By then, the Ferraris started to close in on the McLarens in front of them.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Behind them, Piquet passed Nannini to take fifth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 50, Mansell was close to Senna and passed him to lead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He pulled away fast but then hit Phillipe Alliot while lapping him, pushing the Ligier into a wall while Mansell got away with no damage.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Two laps later, Suzuki and Caffi collided and with the latter stuck in the cockpit in a zone with the wall next to the track, the race was stopped.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Thus Mansell won from Senna, Prost, Berger, Piquet and Nannini.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Qualifying in Spain, at the Jerez circuit near Seville, was marred by a serious incident involving Martin Donnelly.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] During a hot lap on the Friday, the Northern Irishman suffered a suspension failure on one of the fastest corners of the circuit, sending his Lotus into the barriers head-on.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The car was destroyed while Donnelly was thrown across the track with his seat still strapped to his back; he suffered severe leg fractures and bruising on his brain and lungs.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Remarkably, he survived, though his Formula One career was over.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna, shaken by this incident, took his 50th career pole position ahead of Prost, Mansell, Alesi, Berger and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Senna led away from Prost, while Alesi was hit by Patrese and spun into retirement.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell kept up with the championship challengers, while Berger struggled on hard tyres and held up the Williams and Benettons.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The pit stops saw Mansell get ahead of Prost before waving his teammate through; he did so just as Senna was emerging from his own stop.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The Brazilian, realising that he could not afford to be behind Mansell, dived ahead of him.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Piquet, who had not pitted, held a narrow lead over Prost; the Frenchman pressured him into running wide on lap 29, dropping him down to fourth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He eventually retired with battery problems.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna began to struggle with a punctured radiator, and was passed by Mansell before dropping out on lap 54.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Nannini was now up to third while Boutsen and Berger disputed fourth; the two tangled on lap 57, sending Berger into retirement.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Prost and Mansell duly completed a Ferrari 1–2, the Frenchman 22 seconds ahead, with Nannini, Boutsen, Patrese and Suzuki completing the top six.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] With two races to go, Senna had 78 points to Prost's 69; both had had eleven points finishes and would therefore have to drop points if they scored again.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna was still in a strong position, however, as a win or a second place (if Prost did not win) in the next race would give him the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger was third with 40, Mansell was up to fourth with 31 and Boutsen was fifth with 30.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Similarly, McLaren retained a strong position in the Constructors' Championship with 118 points against Ferrari's 100, with Williams a distant third with 49, and Benetton fourth with 47.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Before the Japanese Grand Prix at Suzuka, Nannini was involved in a helicopter crash, suffering a severed right forearm.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Though it was reattached using microsurgery, his F1 career ended.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Meanwhile, the EuroBrun and Life teams withdrew (meaning that pre-qualifying was unnecessary); Benetton duly took on EuroBrun's Roberto Moreno as Nannini's replacement.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] In qualifying, Senna took pole ahead of Prost, Mansell, Berger, Boutsen and Piquet.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] However, Senna was unhappy at the pole being located on the dirty side of the track and thus the second place being on the racing line which should give the second-placed driver the advantage into the first corner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He went to FISA president Jean Marie Balestre to change the side on which pole was located, but was refused.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Prost did have the advantage and Senna attempted to dive into the narrowing gap left by the Frenchman, who drove the normal racing line.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna's left front touched Prost's rear wing, spinning both of them into the gravel trap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Although Senna led by 9 points and there were 9 points for a win, if Prost won the last race he would have had to drop his fifth place in Canada which meant that he would be two points behind Senna even if Senna retired.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] In the race Berger was leading Mansell, Piquet, Moreno, Boutsen and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start of the second lap, Berger spun off into retirement after hitting debris from the Senna-Prost collision.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] This left Mansell who was under pressure by the Benettons leading.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell then began to pull away from Piquet and Moreno as Suzuki passed Warwick for sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell pitted with a 15-second lead on lap 27 for tyres but his driveshaft snapped as he went out of his garage.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] He retired giving the Constructors title to McLaren as they were 18 points ahead and a 1–2 could get only 15 points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The Benettons and Suzuki did not stop but Patrese and Boutsen did with Patrese getting ahead at the stops but both rejoined behind Suzuki.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Then Nakajima passed Warwick to take sixth as Warwick then retired with gearbox trouble.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Piquet won with Moreno making it a Benetton 1–2.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Suzuki was third, Patrese fourth, Boutsen fifth and Nakajima sixth.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The last race of the year was in Australia for what would be the 500th World Championship Grand Prix race, and at the Adelaide City street circuit the McLarens took 1–2 in qualifying ahead of the Ferraris, Senna ahead of Berger, Mansell, Prost, Alesi and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the start, Senna took off into the lead with Berger defending from the Ferraris and Piquet getting by Alesi and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The order was: Senna, Berger, Mansell, Prost, Piquet and Alesi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] On lap 2, Berger accidentally hit the engine kill switch allowing Mansell to get ahead before he could bump start the McLaren.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Then while defending from Prost, he held up Prost allowing Piquet to get ahead of the Frenchman.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Piquet then soon passed Berger for third and the order settled down.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna and Mansell continued to pull away from the rest, none of them able to keep up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Soon Patrese got past Alesi with Boutsen following suit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Then, on lap 43, Mansell went up an escape road, giving Senna a good lead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell was caught and passed by Piquet and pitted for tyres soon after.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] At the stops, Boutsen got ahead of Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Berger then ran wide entering the Brabham straight, allowing Prost to take third.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell passed Berger on lap 57 and soon passed Prost on his new tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Senna had a gearbox glitch on lap 62 and went straight on into the wall and retired.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell closed in on Piquet, breaking the lap record 3 times towards the finish, taking 2 seconds a lap out of his lead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Piquet made an error with 4 laps to go, allowing Mansell to close right up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Mansell attacked on the last lap with a desperate passing attempt at the end of the straight, was too far behind to make the pass.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] Thus, Piquet won from Mansell, Prost, Berger, Boutsen and Patrese.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] In the constructors, McLaren were champions with 121 points with Ferrari second with 110, Benetton third with 71 and Williams fourth with 55.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-formula-one-world-championship] The 1990 season also included a single event which did not count towards the World Championship, the Formula One Indoor Trophy at the Bologna Motor Show.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The **1990 Japanese Grand Prix** was a Formula One motor race held on 21 October 1990 at Suzuka Circuit, the fifteenth and penultimate race of the 1990 Formula One World Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] It was the 16th Japanese Grand Prix and the 6th held at Suzuka.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The race saw a first-corner collision between World Championship rivals Brazilian driver Ayrton Senna and French driver Alain Prost, the second consecutive year that the World Championship had been decided by a collision of Senna coming from behind shunting Prost off the Japanese track.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The race saw a best result to that point for the Benetton Formula team, with their drivers Brazilian veteran Nelson Piquet and his protégé Roberto Moreno finishing first and second in their Benetton B190s.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] It was back to back wins for Benetton in Japan after the team's win the previous year.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Japanese driver Aguri Suzuki scored a career-best result for himself, the Larrousse team and the Lamborghini engine, finishing third in his Lola LC90.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] With Ferrari scoring no points after Nigel Mansell's retirement, the McLaren team secured their sixth and third consecutive Constructors' Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] As of 2026, this was the last race where no European driver finished the race on the podium, and two South American drivers and an Asian driver filled the top three positions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] It was also the only race where the Larrousse team scored a podium finish during their eight seasons of competing in Formula One, and the first and only podium finish for the Lamborghini V12 engine in Formula One.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Suzuki's podium finish was the first for a Japanese driver (later matched by Takuma Sato and Kamui Kobayashi) and the last for a Japanese driver at his home race until Kamui Kobayashi did so at the 2012 Japanese Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Moreover, it was the last of Brazil's eleven one-twos in Formula One, the only one featuring Piquet and Moreno; of the other ten, eight featured Piquet and Senna and the other two had Emerson Fittipaldi and José Carlos Pace.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Before the race, Brabham announced that they would use Yamaha engines for 1991, while Footwork announced a Porsche engine deal for 1991 and retained both their 1990 drivers, Alex Caffi and Michele Alboreto.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Prior to the race, the Life Racing Engines and EuroBrun teams withdrew from the sport.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] EuroBrun's Roberto Moreno joined the Benetton team replacing the previous year's race winner Alessandro Nannini, who was unable to attend the race following a helicopter crash that also ended his Formula One career, one week after the Spanish Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Jean Alesi did not start after suffering a neck injury during Friday's practice.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] As his grid position was left empty, this was the third consecutive race to have only 25 starters instead of the usual 26.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] On Saturday, Soichiro Honda, the founder of Honda, met Ayrton Senna in the McLaren pit.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] After the withdrawal of the EuroBrun and Life teams, there was no need for a pre-qualifying session as only 30 cars remained in the event.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The four drivers relieved of the necessity to pre-qualify, Yannick Dalmas, Gabriele Tarquini (both AGS), Olivier Grouillard (Osella) and Bertrand Gachot (Coloni) were ultimately the four drivers that failed to qualify for the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Gachot crashed heavily in the Friday session.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Roberto Moreno, who had left EuroBrun and joined Benetton, qualified easily in ninth position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Ayrton Senna qualified on pole but was unhappy with the dirty side of the track it was situated on, arguing that pole should always be on the racing line.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] He and Gerhard Berger then went to the Japanese stewards to request a change of position of pole to the cleaner left side of the track.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The stewards initially agreed but a last minute injunction by FISA president Jean Marie Balestre rejected the decision and the original pole position remained on the dirtier right side of the track.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] In addition, the FIA had warned that crossing the yellow line of the pit exit on the right to better position oneself at the first corner would not be permitted, further infuriating Senna.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] At the start, Prost took the lead but Senna attempted to take the inside line into the first corner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The two drivers made contact, sending both off the track and into instant retirement.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The crash meant that Senna had clinched the Drivers' Championship for a second time, as with one race left in the season, Prost could not overtake his points tally.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Benetton-Ford's dominance of the podium prevented Ferrari from scoring enough points to stop McLaren clinching its sixth constructors' title.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] After the collision, the race proceeded with Gerhard Berger's McLaren MP4/5B leading and Nigel Mansell's Ferrari 641 second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] On lap 2, Berger spun off at the first corner on sand thrown onto the track by the Senna/Prost collision, leaving Mansell to lead the race from the two Benettons of Nelson Piquet and Roberto Moreno.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Anticipating that Benetton would follow their usual strategy of not making a pit stop, Mansell built up a gap until he pitted for tyres at the end of lap 26.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] After a quick stop, he left his box with heavy wheelspin, and a driveshaft failed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The Ferrari pulled over at the end of the pit lane and retired.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Piquet inherited the lead and retained it until the chequered flag, with his teammate Moreno following closely, achieving Benetton's first one-two finish.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Aguri Suzuki also drove a non-stop race, finishing third, the first Japanese driver to do so.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The two Williams FW13B-Renaults of Riccardo Patrese and Thierry Boutsen finished fourth and fifth, while Satoru Nakajima finished sixth in a Tyrrell 019, the second Japanese driver in the points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Both Suzuki and Moreno achieved their only career podiums in Formula One.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Prost and Senna discussed the event afterwards, with Senna claiming it was not how he wanted it but how it had to be.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] Prost was infuriated by this, and described the move as "disgusting" and Senna as "a man without value".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] He later said that he almost retired from the sport instantly after the incident.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] After winning his third and final World Championship in 1991, Senna admitted that his move was deliberate, and that it was a payback for 1989.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/1990-japanese-grand-prix] The pair went on to win one more championship each (Senna in 1991 and Prost in 1993) and eventually reconciled their differences on the podium in their final race together at the 1993 Australian Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The **2021 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix** was a Formula One motor race held on 12 December 2021 at the Yas Marina Circuit in Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates and the 13th edition of the Abu Dhabi Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Contested over 58 laps, it was the twenty-second and final round of the 2021 Formula One World Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton had led most of the race and appeared on course to win his eighth title.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Verstappen overtook Hamilton on the final lap after a controversial safety car restart in the last moments of the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Mercedes immediately protested the race result, and the race stewards heard the protest and dismissed it.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Mercedes had the option to appeal the outcome to the FIA International Court of Appeal, but did not do so.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The FIA, the governing authority of the sport, subsequently conducted an inquiry into the race, confirming the race and the championship results.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] It concluded that the rules had been ambiguous and the safety car regulations required clarification.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The FIA issued a press statement stating that race director Michael Masi had acted "in good faith and to the best of his knowledge given the difficult circumstances".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The inquiry lead to a clarification of the safety car regulations, communications between the teams and race control were limited, and the role of the race director was restructured, with Masi being replaced by two new people.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The Grand Prix was the final race for 2007 world champion Kimi Räikkönen; the then 42-year-old Finn retired from Formula One after a two-decade career spanning a then-record 349 Grand Prix starts.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This was also the final race for Honda as a works power unit supplier until the 2026 Australian Grand Prix in partnership with Aston Martin.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The race was originally scheduled to take place on 5 December, but was rescheduled to 12 December after the postponement of the Australian Grand Prix due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Its original date was eventually taken by the Saudi Arabian Grand Prix while the Australian race was cancelled and replaced by the Qatar Grand Prix.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] It thus became the 22nd and last race of the 2021 season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The Yas Marina Circuit underwent a layout change that shortened the track in order to increase top speeds and overtaking opportunities.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The chicane after turn 4 was removed, and the turn 5 hairpin (turn 7 before redevelopment) was widened.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The four corner sequence of turns which were turns 11–14 became one single banked turn 9.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The radii of turns 12–15 (previously 17–20) were increased to allow cars to carry more speed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The changes to turn 15 allowed cars to be able to travel flat out through the corner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Sole tyre supplier Pirelli provided the C3, C4, and C5 tyre compounds—the softest selections available—for use in dry conditions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Jack Aitken participated for Williams in the first practice session in place of George Russell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Nikita Mazepin tested positive for COVID-19 after qualifying, forcing his withdrawal from the race; he was not replaced.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The Grand Prix marked the last Formula One race for 2007 world champion Kimi Räikkönen, who had announced his intention of retiring at the end of the 2021 season a few months earlier, ending his Formula One career after 19 seasons to move to NASCAR Cup Series.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] As of 2025, it is also the last race of Antonio Giovinazzi, who moved to Formula E, and Mazepin, whose contract was terminated following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine and the cancellation of Uralkali's title sponsorship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] It was also the final race for Russell and Valtteri Bottas at Williams and Mercedes-AMG, respectively, as they moved to Mercedes and Alfa Romeo Racing.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Bottas raced with a special helmet for the occasion, featuring photos of all the moments he spent at Mercedes, and he sported a special set of blue racing overalls.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Alpine featured the words "El Plan" in both their cars referencing a popular Internet meme.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This race also marked the last race for Honda as official engine supplier, as Red Bull Racing and AlphaTauri raced with Red Bull Powertrains from 2022, until their return at the 2026 Australian Grand Prix with Aston Martin.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Title rivals Max Verstappen (Red Bull Racing) and Lewis Hamilton (Mercedes-AMG) both entered the round with 369.5 points, leaving the championship contenders level on points for the final round for the first time since 1974 and only the second time in the sport's history.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This meant the driver who scored the most points would win the championship; if both drivers had scored an equal amount of points, Verstappen would have won the championship owing to having more race wins (nine to Hamilton's eight prior to the race).
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The Drivers' Championship was decided in the final round for the 30th time and the first time since 2016.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the Constructors' Championship, with 44 points on the table for every team, Mercedes led with 587.5 points, 28 ahead of Red Bull on 559.5; this was the first time since 2008 that the final round of the season decided the Constructors' Championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the midfield, Scuderia Ferrari led McLaren in the battle for third place by a margin of 38.5 points.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Acrimonious on-track battles throughout the season led to concerns that one of the drivers might cause a deliberate in-race collision in an attempt to win the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Three practice sessions were scheduled over the course of the weekend.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The first session took place at 13:30 local time (UTC+04:00) on Friday 10 December.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The third session took place at 14:00 on Saturday, 11 December.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The first practice session passed without incident and ended with Verstappen setting the fastest time, followed by Bottas and Hamilton.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The second practice session ended with Hamilton fastest by 0.3 seconds to second-placed Esteban Ocon, while Bottas was third fastest ahead of Verstappen, 0.6 seconds behind Hamilton.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Räikkönen crashed at turn 14 just as the session was concluding, but was unhurt.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Qualifying started at 17:00 local time on Saturday, 11 December.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The first qualifying session was briefly suspended after Mick Schumacher collided with a bollard but was resumed without further incident, with the Mercedes drivers Hamilton and Bottas recording the fastest times.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the second session, initial flying laps on medium-compound tyres gave Hamilton a four-millisecond advantage over Red Bull Racing driver Verstappen.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] A lock-up on his second flying lap led to Verstappen's return to the pits for soft tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] At the end of the session, Verstappen had improved to take first place on the timesheets.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Having set the time on the faster soft-compound tyres he was locked to starting the race on Sunday with them, as Hamilton was likewise locked into using his more durable medium-compound tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the third and final qualifying session, Verstappen was able to use the slipstream of his teammate Sergio Pérez to secure pole position, with Hamilton taking the second spot on the grid.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The race started at 17:00 local time on Sunday, 12 December with an attendance of 153,000.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton immediately took the lead from Verstappen on the main straight.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Verstappen attempted an overtake at the turn 6-7 chicane on the inside.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Verstappen's trajectory and late braking took him to the far outside of the track, Hamilton, still on the right, cut turn 7, claiming that Verstappen forced him off.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton re-joined considerably further ahead of Verstappen than where he was before the corner.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Red Bull Racing protested, arguing that he should have ceded the position to Verstappen, but were told by radio that Hamilton had ultimately given back any advantage gained.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The incident was referred to the stewards, who decided that no further investigation was necessary, something Horner called "a total lack of consistency" mid-race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton then utilised the durability of his medium-compound tyres to extend his lead over Verstappen, whose soft-compound tyres were suffering from greater degradation.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Verstappen made his stop at the end of lap 13 with Hamilton following suit one lap later, both opting for a set of the hardest tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This elevated Pérez to P1, with the Mexican driver being instructed on radio to hold Hamilton up to allow for Verstappen to catch up.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This reduced the gap between the contenders from about 11 seconds after the pits to 1.3 seconds on lap 21.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton proceeded to extend the gap again to four seconds by the midpoint of the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On lap 26, Alfa Romeo's Räikkönen collided with the barriers at turn 6 due to brake issues, prompting his retirement in his 349th and final Formula One race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On the same lap, Russell retired in his final race for Williams due to gearbox issues.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On lap 35, Giovinazzi retired his car alongside the track for the same reason as Russell, triggering a brief virtual safety car period.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Red Bull used this opportunity to pit Verstappen in for a fresh set of the hard-compound tyres without losing track position; Mercedes, wary to give up track position, did not pit Hamilton.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Though Verstappen gradually reduced the post-stop deficit from seventeen seconds to eleven, he was not on track to catch Hamilton before the end of the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On lap 53, Nicholas Latifi, who was fighting with Haas' Mick Schumacher for 15th place and had dirty tyres after going off circuit at turn 9, crashed at turn 14 and the safety car was deployed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton again did not pit because he did not have a sufficient gap to Verstappen, with the team possibly expecting the race to end under the safety car.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Meanwhile, Verstappen pitted for soft tyres, retaining second position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Pérez retired to the pits to prevent a possible retirement on track.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] As the debris from Latifi's crash was being cleared by the race marshals, the lapped drivers were initially informed that they would not be permitted to overtake.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On lap 57, the penultimate lap, Horner complained over radio to Masi to get "these lapped cars out of the way".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Masi then directed the five lapped cars between Hamilton and Verstappen specifically to overtake the safety car, unlike the lapped cars behind Verstappen, which stayed in position.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This had never happened before, as previously either none or all lapped cars followed this procedure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] There did not appear to be enough time left to restart the race, as regulations stipulated the safety car to return to the pits at the end of the *following* lap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Immediately after Vettel joined the lead lap by passing Hamilton and the safety car, however, race control announced the safety car would enter the pits at the end of the *current* lap, allowing for one more lap of green flag conditions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] This caused angry remonstrations from Mercedes team principal Toto Wolff: "Michael, this isn’t right!" Verstappen overtook Hamilton into turn 5 to win both the race and the 2021 World Drivers' Championship, with Hamilton in second.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Over the radio, Wolff appealed to Masi to reinstate the order of the penultimate lap, to which Masi replied: "Toto, it's called a motor race, ok?
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Ferrari driver Carlos Sainz Jr. finished in third, AlphaTauri driver Yuki Tsunoda in a career-best fourth place.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the laps before the safety car, Hamilton was leading comfortably and looked all but set to win the race and the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The chaotic final laps produced multiple controversial incidents and decisions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] While the last point was dismissed on the grounds that Verstappen was not ahead at the end of the safety car period, the other issues were more contentious.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] If this had been complied with, so Mercedes' argument goes, Hamilton would have won the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] They thus requested that the classification be amended as such.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Masi argued that Article 48.12 was intended to remove cars that "interfered" with drivers racing on the lead lap and that all teams had earlier, in principle, agreed that all races should end under racing conditions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Verstappen was confirmed as world champion, pending any appeal.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Mercedes initially announced their intention to appeal to the FIA International Court of Appeal citing potential breaches of Article 15 of the International Sporting Code and Article 10 of the FIA Judicial and Disciplinary Code.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On 15 December, the FIA announced that it would conduct a "detailed analysis and clarification exercise" of the event, investigating the running of the race to determine if adjustments to the safety car procedures were needed.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] They further stated that there was a "significant misunderstanding" about the rules by some of the teams, drivers and fans, an allegation for which they were criticised by journalist Scott Mitchell.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The FIA admitted that the ongoing controversy was "tarnishing the image" of the sport.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] One day later, Mercedes announced that they would not to pursue an appeal, hours before a submission deadline, vowing to hold the FIA "accountable" nonetheless.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Wolff explained that neither he nor Hamilton wished to be awarded the championship in court, and Mercedes would instead focus their efforts to ensure an equitable result from the investigation.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Wolff remained heavily critical of Masi.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In particular, Wolff criticised Masi's race control in Abu Dhabi as being inconsistent with his handling of the 2020 Eifel Grand Prix, where Masi had claimed the Sporting Regulations mandated that all lapped cars must unlap themselves, and expressed his indignation at the perceived injustice.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Both Wolff and Hamilton boycotted the FIA Prize Giving Ceremony.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton was later fined for not attending; he asked the FIA to donate the money towards the work the body carries out with underprivileged children.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Amid speculation that Hamilton might announce a snap retirement due to disillusionment with the events, Wolff indicated both he and his driver would continue in the sport after a period of reflection in the off-season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] An expert on international arbitration and litigation suggested in *The Guardian* that Mercedes would have been in a strong position to mount legal action.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] They described the dismissal of Mercedes' initial challenge to the results as the FIA "marking its own homework" and further noted the conflict between a desire to stress sporting integrity and the increased commercialisation of the sport.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] While expressing sympathy to the notion of accepting the outcome of a race on the track, he suspected that Mercedes would "not have any choice" but to appeal.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Another lawyer, Nicholas Bamber, concurred in saying there was a "good legal basis" for an appeal, and that he believes an apparent inconsistency in the implementation of regulations could prove difficult to justify.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In January 2022, the BBC reported that Mercedes had reached a *quid pro quo* agreement with the FIA, in which Masi and Formula One's technical director Nikolas Tombazis would not be in the same position for the 2022 season, in exchange for dropping their appeal.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Wolff would also have a personal meeting with FIA president Mohammed Ben Sulayem to discuss the way forward.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Drivers were expected to cite what they perceived to be a lenient attitude by Masi and race stewards towards Verstappen's driving during the 2021 season, with Andrew Benson of BBC Sport saying this could result in a harder line on driving standards in the future.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In the immediate post-race interview, Hamilton congratulated Verstappen and his family on his first World Drivers' Championship, as did his father Anthony.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Wolff congratulated Verstappen via text message.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Several drivers expressed discontent over what had transpired.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In a last-lap radio message to his race engineer Peter Bonnington, which was not played on the television feed, Hamilton said the race had been "manipulated".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Russell, who was signed to be Hamilton's teammate at Mercedes in 2022, called the decisions of Michael Masi "unacceptable".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Norris, one of the five drivers permitted to unlap themselves, said the decision to go racing again on the last lap was made "for TV".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The four other drivers, Alonso, Ocon, Leclerc, and Vettel, also expressed confusion at the sudden instruction to unlap.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Daniel Ricciardo, the first driver not permitted to unlap himself, said he was "speechless" at the instruction, which prevented him to race other drivers on newer soft-compound tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Sainz Jr., who was positioned behind Ricciardo and Lance Stroll upon the restart, immediately under pressure from Tsunoda, Pierre Gasly, and Bottas behind, opined that the decision to resume racing under the circumstances "nearly cost [him his] podium".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Speaking at Aston Martin's 2022 car launch in February 2022, Stroll described the Abu Dhabi situation as "ridiculous", articulating that rules should be set in stone before a season starts.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Masi's decisions were widely criticised as unusual and to contrive excitement.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] 1996 world champion Damon Hill commented that the decision appeared without precedent, stating that it was "a new way of running the sport, where the race director can make these *ad hoc* decisions".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] 2016 world champion Nico Rosberg felt that Masi "did not follow the rules" and Horner demanding "one more lap of racing" to Masi via radio was inappropriate.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Writing for Fox Sports, Jack Austin stated that Formula One "engineered" the finish out of a "desperation for drama".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Jordan Bianchi of *The Athletic* echoed a similar sentiment, suggesting that Masi's decision was to ensure that "Netflix gets another juicy storyline for the next season of *Drive to Survive*", and also questioned his capability in effectively officiating a race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Former racing driver Susie Wolff was in "disbelief" over Masi having "[interpreted] the rules in a way that had never been applied before".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In particular, the fairness of Masi's decision to diverge from standard safety car procedures was extensively debated.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Swedish former racing driver, Stefan Johansson, commented: "Whether it's intentional or not, the entertainment value of this controversy has gone through the roof.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] But I think there has to be a balance somewhere because the decisions Masi made (...) completely ignored any level of common sense as to what would have been a fair way to handle the situation".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] India's first Formula One driver, Narain Karthikeyan claimed: "It was a great battle for the championship but what happened yesterday, it wasn't sport.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] You need close battles in Formula One but it has to be fair at the same time (...) What happened was not fair".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] German former rally champion Walter Röhrl called for races to be decided on the track or in a "fair, clear process that is not influenced by any opaque external decisions".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Dutch former Formula One driver Christijan Albers also raised the issue of fairness: "Michael Masi seemed a bit unsure at a few races last year.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] But he certainly played a decisive role in the final leg of the season, which left many in bewilderment.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Everyone wanted the season finale to be fair".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Labour peer and vice-chairman of the All Party Parliamentary Group on Formula One, Peter Hain, commented that the events at the finale were not good for the sport.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He said: "It may be exciting and it may be dramatic, it may gain the audiences that Formula One craves, but you have to think of the credibility and the integrity of the sport in the longer term (...) the FIA can't afford to have Formula One tarnished in this way".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Several analysts highlighted that Masi's decision had direct bearings on the championship results.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Andrew Benson, again writing for the BBC, opined in March 2022 that if Masi had allowed all lapped cars to unlap themselves, the race would not have restarted at all, and Hamilton would have won both the race and the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Sky Sports F1 commentator David Croft assessed that Hamilton would have won the race and the championship had "the rules been adhered to as they are written".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Former driver Karun Chandhok, however, stated that Verstappen could have won the championship even if the normal procedure had been followed "had the lapped cars gone past before the end of lap 56".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Others drew attention to the amount of psychological pressure Masi would have been under.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Dutch newspaper *De Volkskrant* made note of the immense pressure on a Formula One race director to make snap decisions, and expressed sympathy with Masi on that basis.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Former driver Romain Grosjean defended Masi's decision and commented: "There's a few ways of seeing it.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] It would have been very strange to not unlap those cars and have Lewis first and then Max four cars behind over one lap for the world championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] And, on the other hand, for Lewis it was definitely not a great call.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] But as a TV fan, as a spectator, as for the sport, I think Michael Masi made the right decision." Less forgivingly, Karthikeyan questioned Masi's ability to handle pressure.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Horner defended Masi's decision making, claiming that Mercedes lost the race due to tactical errors instead.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Karthikeyan argued Mercedes had made the right strategic decisions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Mercedes has particularly been subject to criticism for not pitting Hamilton during the safety car, leaving him vulnerable on the final lap with old tyres.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] According to former team manager Peter Windsor, Mercedes assumed the race would end under safety car conditions, which did not happen only because "the FIA did not follow its own rules", something that was impossible for Mercedes to predict.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Wolff later professed that while he himself had always tried to look at things from the other side, Horner was "never able to admit" that Masi had been in the wrong that day.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Dutch newspaper *NRC Handelsblad* noted the role luck had played throughout the whole season, and that it was not Verstappen's fault that his win had "become tainted with controversy".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] It was also lamented how a "most beautiful" season had deserved a better ending.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Verstappen later stated that he does not care about people thinking his title is tarnished.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Wolff, however critical of the means, described Verstappen as a "worthy champion".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On 17 December 2021, bin Sulayem hinted at changes to avoid such controversy in the future, and did not rule out the possibility of removing Masi from his role as race director.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On 13 January 2022, it was reported that the FIA was considering making changes to the safety car procedures as well as its own internal operational structure within Formula One after the FIA launched a consultation with all ten Formula One teams on "various issues".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In line with the deal that had Mercedes drop their appeal, the FIA published new guidelines ahead of the 2022 season which included stricter rules on wheel-to-wheel combat as well as stricter enforcement of track limits through revised phrasings.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Former Formula One driver-turned commentator Martin Brundle commented that "removing Masi won't solve F1's credibility concerns" caused by the incident, but three-time Grand Prix winner Johnny Herbert felt Masi had done "too much damage" to the sport's reputation and should be replaced.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Motorspors news website *The Race* and Sky Sports also ran similar stories on Masi being replaced.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] *The Race*'s article further stated that some of the responsibilities of the race director could be reassigned to different personnel.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] FIA secretary General Peter Bayer stated that the race director had "too much" to cope with.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Bayer also stated that Masi could stay with the organisation in another capacity.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Following its investigation and a meeting of the F1 Commission on 14 February 2022 the FIA said it would reveal an 'action plan' for structural changes within its organisation later that same week.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Radio transmissions between teams and the FIA will no longer be broadcast on television to ease pressure on race officials.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The FIA subsequently revealed regulation changes regarding safety car procedures to be used from the 2022 season onwards.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Under these changes rather than waiting until the lap after the last car has unlapped itself from the leader, the safety car will now be withdrawn one lap after the instruction that lapped cars may unlap themselves has been given.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In March 2022, the FIA published their official report.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The FIA report also concluded that the communication between the team principals of Mercedes and Red Bull with Masi during the final laps was inappropriate, and recommended changes be made "in order to protect the Race Director from any pressure and allow him to take decisions peacefully".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Further recommendations were made to clarify the safety car regulations.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The report significantly contributed to reforms by FIA President Mohammed Ben Sulayem aimed at restructuring and modernising race operations.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] After the final report was presented to the World Motor Sport Council, the FIA issued a press statement stating *(inter alia)* that race director Michael Masi had acted "in good faith and to the best of his knowledge given the difficult circumstances".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Verstappen finished the season eight points ahead of Hamilton as the first Red Bull driver since 2013 to win the championship.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He was also the first in a Honda-powered car to do so since Senna in 1991.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Mercedes won their eighth consecutive Constructors' title, extending their own record.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] It was the first time since 2008, when Hamilton had won for McLaren, that the Driver's champion had not been driving for the Constructors' champions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Immediately after the race, Nicholas Latifi apologised for causing the crash that led to the controversial safety car period.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Over the ensuing days, Latifi stated that he received abuse and death threats from people on social media and condemned the online abuse.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] A few months later, Latifi revealed that he had received messages of support from Lewis Hamilton and that he had to be accompanied by additional personal security when attending events ahead of the 2022 season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He also confirmed personal plans to highlight the effect on mental health that online abuse can have on people.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On 11 January 2022, the BBC reported that Hamilton was considering his future in the sport pending the outcome of the FIA report, with the Formula One paddock expecting the FIA to take significant action as a result of the race.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] According to Benson, Mercedes denied claims that they dropped their post race appeal after being assured that Masi would step down or be removed from his role.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] On the same day, Formula One journalist Mark Hughes noted that Hamilton's silence since the race had echoes of Ayrton Senna's past feud with the governing body after the championship deciders in 1989 and 1990.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Mitchell commented that the Abu Dhabi situation was just one part of a wider dissatisfaction from teams with how the FIA had begun to apply regulations in the seasons following Masi's appointment in 2019.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] McLaren CEO Zak Brown said the sport should not just automatically assume that Hamilton was going to stay on in the sport for 2022, though Brown personally expected him to contest it.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] The 1997 world champion Jacques Villeneuve speculated that Hamilton was staying silent because he was trying to distance himself from Mercedes boss Toto Wolff, perhaps considering a career in the film industry.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton subsequently broke his silence, and continued to race in the 2022 season.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He went 30 months without a win, doubting himself, and taking a toll on his mental health.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Michael Masi has also been subject to social media abuse and death threats as a result of the controversies due to which he sought support for his mental health.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] During the 2023 Australian Grand Prix, Masi wished to meet Hamilton in an effort to explain his momentous decisions.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Hamilton declined, as there was "nothing to say".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In 2024, Red Bull CTO Adrian Newey reflected on how Abu Dhabi left a psychological effect on Mercedes and they were unable to move on.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Susie Wolff, Toto Wolff's wife, has revealed that the impact of Abu Dhabi "weighed heavily on [her] for a long time".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] Toto Wolff has stated he has "never spoken with Masi since the race" and 'did not wish to ever speak to him again'.
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He has described the sudden, contradictory turns of events in the final few minutes of the race as a "nightmare", revealed how they became a taboo in the family for a time, and predicted that Lewis and him would "never overcome the pain and the distress".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] He believes the infamous events of December 2021 will leave a legacy on Formula One, and the 2021 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix "will never be forgotten".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] By denying Hamilton an eighth title, so Wolff suggests, Masi had 'destroyed the record of the greatest champion of all time', describing Masi as a "lunatic".
[src:2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix/2021-abu-dhabi-grand-prix] In an interview with *The Telegraph* almost exactly four years after the ominius event, Wolff revealed that both he and Hamilton still think about Abu Dhabi "every day".
